<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Agrees to Help Develop Egypt's Metallurgical </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Egypt and Japan signed here on
Tuesday a memorandum of understanding on cooperation in developing
and modernizing Egypt's metallurgical technology.
</P>
<P>
The memo was signed between the Egyptian Metallurgical Research
Center, representing the Egyptian government, and the official
Japanese International Cooperation Agency, Egypt's Middle East
News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Adel Nofal, head of the center, told reporters after the
signing ceremony that the memo stipulates that Japan will transfer
advanced technology in forming, cutting and welding metals to
Egypt's small and medium industries.
</P>
<P>
The small and medium enterprises, which account for 99.7
percent of Egypt's non-agricultural private businesses, provide 80
percent of the value produced annually by the private sector and
employ 75 percent of the labor force.
</P>
<P>
Of the 550,000 new jobs that Egypt hopes to create each year
until 2017, according to a government document, "Egypt in the 21st
Century," the country's small and medium enterprises are supposed
to come up with 325,000.
</P>
<P>
Under the memo, Japan will provide training opportunities to
young researchers of the Egyptian center at its research centers
and plants, Nofal said.
</P>
<P>
Japanese metallurgical experts will visit Egypt to give
lectures to Egyptian researchers under the memo.
</P>
<P>
Cooperation between the center and the Japanese agency began in
1985 when they set up a department for inspection and welding at
the center, the news agency said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
