<HEADLINE> Council Supports Dialogue to Solve Prevlaka Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 20 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council
Tuesday reiterated its support for the process of negotiations
between Croatia and the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia (FRY) to
solve their dispute over the Prevlaka Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
Council members "regretted that substantial progress so far has
not been achieved, and called upon them to intensify their efforts
in this regard," said France's Alain Dejammet, April president of
the Council, after it met to deal with the matter Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The 15-member Council discussed U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan's April 9 report on the situation in Prevlaka.
</P>
<P>
Annan said Croatia and the FRY have already put forward their
own initiatives on the resolution of their dispute after four
rounds of bilateral talks since 1996.
</P>
<P>
The latest talks were conducted in Belgrade on March 9 with no
substantial progress achieved.
</P>
<P>
However, both sides have stated their intention to continue
discussions, the report said.
</P>
<P>
"The assistance of the United Nations in the search for a
peaceful settlement of the issue has yet to be utilized," it
added.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has maintained 27 military observers in Prevlaka.
Their mission is due to end on July 15. 
</P>
</TEXT>
