<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sweden to Finance Tanzanian Power Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania and Sweden Tuesday
signed a 8.6-million-U.S. dollar agreement in which the latter
will finance rehabilitation of the Ubungo Power Sub-station in
Tanzanian capital Dar es Salaam.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed by Swedish Ambassador to Tanzania Sten
Rylander and the Permanent Secretary in Tanzania's Ministry of
Energy and Minerals, Patrick Rutabanzibwa.
</P>
<P>
The improvement work of the substation will include
rehabilitation and expansion of the high voltage parts and key
components of the switchyard to secure availability, reliability
and safety of the sub-station, Rutabanzibwa said.
</P>
<P>
He said the rehabilitation of the 33-kilovolt switchyard will
also ensure the best utilization of the two gas turbines and
capacitor banks previously installed at Ubungo with Swedish
government's assistance.
</P>
<P>
The rehabilitation is envisaged to be finalized by the end of
next year, said the permanent secretary.
</P>
<P>
"The sub-station at Ubungo is considered to be the most
critical point in the whole electrical network of Tanzania," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Over the past year, the electric power demand in Dar es Salaam
and Zanzibar has grown considerably without much increase in the
capacity of the Ubungo sub-station, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Operational problems with outdated equipment at Ubungo have
caused a number of power outage and failures, he said.
</P>
<P>
The permanent secretary said that the Swedish contribution to
the energy sector has been immense over the last 30 years,
amounting to 140 billion shillings (about two million U.S. dollars
at current prices). Sweden's total assistance to Tanzania stand
at 1,615 billion shillings.
</P>
<P>
Sweden financed the Kidatu Hydro-power Station in 1970 and has
subsequently assisted in funding several other hydro-electrical
power projects, he said.
</P>
<P>
Ambassador Rylander reiterated his country's commitment to
remaining as a strong and reliable partner of Tanzania in the
energy sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
