<HEADLINE> Former Greek Premier Criticizes Western Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Former Greek Prime Minister
Constantine Mitsotakis Tuesday criticized the West for apparently
taking sides in the Kosovo conflict.
</P>
<P>
In a statement released here Tuesday, Mitsotakis, who was
Greece's premier in 1990-1993, said that the West must be an
objective observer which impartially defended peace and human
rights and did not become the ally of one side.
</P>
<P>
The danger of a generalized war the Balkan region was facing
now were grounded in the Rambouillet talks when Western forces
bowed to separatism and added terms that no sovereign country
could have accepted, he said, adding that their rejection by
Belgrade was the pretext for the bombing to begin.
</P>
<P>
He said that the support of an armed struggle by an illegal
separatist group was a particularly dangerous development for the
Balkan region.
</P>
<P>
The former premier also urged Greek Prime Minister Costas
Simitis to seize the opportunity at the NATO summit in Washington
to appeal for another chance at a political settlement of the
conflict in Kosovo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
