<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Govt Refuses To Withdraw Tobacco Levy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's Finance Minister
Herbert Murerwa Tuesday said the government will not immediately
withdraw the five percent tobacco levy charged on growers and
buyers but will review it in the 2000 budget statement to be
announced in October.
</P>
<P>
Murerwa's announcement at the official launch of the tobacco
selling season which sets off Wednesday in Harare came in the wake
of an outcry by tobacco farmers for an immediate reprieve from
levy.
</P>
<P>
The farmers citing already high production costs had threatened
to withhold delivery of their crop until the levy introduced
through a 1996 statutory instrument was removed.
</P>
<P>
The minister said it was not possible for him to unilaterally
announce a reprieve insisting that he had to make his
recommendations to parliament which would approve.
</P>
<P>
President of the Zimbabwe Tobacco Association Richard Tate said
farmers were disappointed because Murerwa's statement was not
strong enough.
</P>
<P>
He said the intended boycott would not take place, but there
would be a slow movement in the sales.
</P>
<P>
"After this statement, we will see a reduction in production
for the next season," he said.
</P>
<P>
Lands and Agriculture Minister Kumbirai Kangai, who will launch
the selling season, said the total exports for 1999 are expected
to be approximately 180,000 tons with a value of about 550 million
U.S. dollars compared with some 176,000 tons exported last year.
</P>
<P>
Tobacco is the country's biggest foreign currency earner.
</P>
</TEXT>
