<HEADLINE> Greece Has Not Decided Over NATO Troops' Transit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Greece had not decided whether it
would allow NATO troops to cross its territory for possible ground
operations against Yugoslavia, Greek government spokesman Nikos
Athanassakis said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Greece hoped that this issue would not be one it had to deal
with, the spokesman said at a press briefing.
</P>
<P>
He also denied reports of plans for NATO war games in Greece,
saying that the only NATO exercise which related to Greece was a
scheduled geographical exercise for 52 officers.
</P>
<P>
So far, Greece, both member of NATO and the European Union
(EU), has refused to participate in NATO's airstrikes against
Yugoslavia and has repeatedly said that it would not send troops
to take part in NATO's possible land operations in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Most of Greeks oppose the NATO bombing raids on Yugoslavia and
they have protested in different forms against NATO's military
actions.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, some 42 members of a Greek trade union movement
said that they would go to Serbia this week to participate in
"human shields" the Yugoslav people are forming around hospitals
and bridges to protect them from NATO bombings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
