<DOCNO> XIE19990421.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Lebanon, Israel Run Into New Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon and its long-time
neighboring rival Israel are getting bogged down in a new dispute
over the village Arnoun in south Lebanon, worsening the already
fragile situation in the border area.
</P>
<P>
The row began when Israel first captured and fenced off Arnoun
with barbed wire in February, claiming it had been used by
Lebanese guerrillas for bombing attacks against Israeli troops
manning the outpost in the Crusader-era Beaufor Castle on the edge
of the Israeli-occupied zone in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Some Israeli soldiers were killed or wounded in and around the
village. And just three days ago, an Israeli solider was killed in
a Hezbollah roadside bomb blast.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of angry university students tore down the barbed wire
fence with their bare hands eight days later after the first
capture.
</P>
<P>
Last Thursday, a 20-man Israeli infantry team and Israel's
militia ally South Lebanon Army (SLA) descended on Arnoun from a
hilltop base at the Beaufort Castle.
</P>
<P>
They set up sandbagged checkpoints, erected earth mounds and
fortifications, and ringed the village with a three-kilometer
barbed-wire fence, effectively re-annexing Arnoun into the
occupied zone.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up the self-styled security zone in 1985 with the
claimed aim of protecting its north from Lebanese guerrillas'
cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah, or Party of God, has since been spearheading a
guerrilla war to drive the Israeli occupation troops and SLA out
of Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Israel's re-capture of Arnoun, where there are only 70
remaining residents, mostly the elderly and children, provoked
strong reaction from Lebanon. Prime Minister Salim Hoss appealed
to the U.N., the U.S. and France to intervene against Israel's
expansion of its occupation zone.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese government has filed a complaint to the
five-nation monitoring committee, which consists of
representatives from U.S., France, Syria, Israel and Lebanon,
demanding that the Jewish state return the village immediately.
</P>
<P>
But, the committee has so far failed to reach an agreement on
whether Israel's occupation of Arnoun constituted a violation of a
1996 cease-fire understanding.
</P>
<P>
The U.S.-brokered truce pact after a 16-day Israeli blitz on
Lebanon in April, 1996, prohibits Israel and Hezbollah from
launching any attacks on civilian targets or from civilian areas
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Israel has reportedly offered to Lebanon through the U.S. that
it will withdraw from Arnoun on the condition that Lebanese army
must be deployed into the village.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese President Emile Lahoud flatly rejected the offer,
saying he will never to let the Lebanese army serve as a guard of
occupation.
</P>
<P>
"(Israeli Prime Minister) Benjamin Netanyahu is trying to drag
Lebanon into security arrangements for the entire occupied zone,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
Last April, Israel suggested that if Beirut agreed with
negotiated security arrangements, it would withdraw from south
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon and its ally Syria rejected the proposal, asking the
Jewish state to leave the country unconditionally in line with
relevant U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
Hoss said Lebanon was not willing to throw its army into a
direct confrontation with the Israeli enemy in Arnoun because that
will involve risks Lebanon can not take.
</P>
<P>
When Lebanon's diplomatic efforts seem to lose its momentum,
Lebanese students are considering to stage another mass march in
the village to repeat their February feat.
</P>
<P>
But, Israel has warned that any civil actions will "be met with
a very firm response." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
