<HEADLINE> Egypt, Russia to Discuss Mideast Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa said on Tuesday that his upcoming talks with Russian
counterpart Igor Ivanov will tackle the latest developments in the
Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Ivanov is scheduled to arrive in Cairo on Friday for a working
visit as part of a regional tour, which will also take him to
Syria, Lebanon, the Palestinian self-rule areas and Israel.
</P>
<P>
Moussa told reporters that they will discuss the Palestinian
plan to declare an independent state and the stalemate in the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat previously announced that he
would declare an independent Palestinian state on May 4 when the
five-year Palestinian interim autonomy enshrined in the Oslo
Accord signed with Israel in 1993 expires.
</P>
<P>
But many countries have advised Arafat to put off the plan so
as to avoid further complicating the stalled peace process.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on a Russian initiative calling for postponement of
the Palestinian plan for six months, Moussa said that he will
listen to the Russian view in this regard.
</P>
<P>
He added the talks will also dwell on the ongoing airstrikes
against Yugoslavia launched by the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization on March 24.
</P>
<P>
NATO unleashed an intensive campaign to punish Belgrade's
refusal to accept an agreement with independence-seeking Kosovo
Albanians which will allow NATO troops into the Serbian province
of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Moussa expressed confidence that Russia could play a vital
political role in helping solve the Kosovo issue in the light of
its distinguished relations with Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
He underlined the importance of the international efforts to
seek a solution to the Kosovo crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
