<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study: Broad Beans Might Help Prevent Bowel Cancer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Broad bean might help protect
against bowel cancer, the second most common cause of deaths for
cancer in the developed world, British scientists said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Researchers from Hammersmith Hospital and the Imperial College
of Science, Technology and Medicine, London, found that a
substance contained in broad bean was able to halt or even reverse
the bowel cancer process.
</P>
<P>
Their study, published in the British journal Gut, has assessed
the effects of dietary lectins on the behavior of cancer cells in
the colon.
</P>
<P>
Lectins, the proteins found in many plant foods including broad
beans, can attach themselves to carbohydrate molecules, which are
then absorbed by the cells lining the bowel during digestion.
</P>
<P>
The new findings showed that broad bean and mushroom lectins
were able to increase differentiations in cancer cells, indicating
that the cancer process was either halted or reversed.
</P>
<P>
The lectins also seemed to inhibit cell multiplication, another
hallmark of cancer cells, the researchers discovered.
</P>
<P>
"It is well known that diets high in fruits and vegetables
protect against many types of cancer, including bowel cancer. The
lectin effect may be one of the reasons why," said Professor
Calam, who led the research. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990421.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Study Blames Boats for Adult Leukaemia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 20 (Xinhua) -- People who build boats or sail in
them are at extra risk of developing leukaemia, British scientists
suggested Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
A report published in the Journal of Epidemiology and Community
Health showed that coastal areas in Britain, where there is a lot
of boating activity, have a higher number of leukaemia cases than
other regions of the country.
</P>
<P>
The study, carried out by the Institute of Public Health at
Cambridge University, is similar to those of earlier studies which
showed that people who live near river estuaries were more prone
to develop leukaemia.
</P>
<P>
But unlike the previous research which attributed the cancers
to heavy metals found in the estuaries, the Cambridge team
believed that the level of maritime activity might be to blame.
</P>
<P>
Boat building and repair are important sources of employment in
the coastal regions in Britain for both recreational and
occupational purposes, the researchers said.
</P>
<P>
"Such activity would involve potential exposure to resins,
solvents and petroleum products, all of which have been linked to
the development of acute leukaemia," they wrote in the report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990421.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
