<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Predicts 2.3 percent Growth Rate for World Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 20 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary
Fund (IMF) predicted a 2.3 percent growth rate for the world
economy this year and 3.4 percent for the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
"Since the end of 1998 some significant positive developments
in the world economy have been broadly balanced by some important
setbacks, so that the global outlook is little changed," said the
latest "World Economic Outlook" (WEO) which was issued by the IMF
here Tuesday. The world economic growth rate stood at 2.5 percent
last year.
</P>
<P>
However, the IMF sees the prospects for a recovery in Asia and
some limits on growth-dampening damage from other regional
contagion effects, although the balance of global economic risks
still appears to be tilted toward the downside.
</P>
<P>
"After the deep output contractions in Asia's crisis-afflicted
economies, activity has recently turned around in Korea and seems
to have bottomed out in Malaysia and Thailand," the IMF said in
the WEO, which was released in advance of its annual spring
meetings.
</P>
<P>
On the positive side of the world economy, the IMF said,
"Investor sentiment toward many emerging market economies has
rallied. Conditions in Mature financial markets also have
improved."
</P>
<P>
"The introduction of the euro has proceeded smoothly," the IMF
said. "Most of the advanced economies of North America and Europe,
and also Australia, have proved resilient to the crisis in
emerging markets. Particularly notable has been the continued
strong growth of the U.S. economy."
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, inflation has generally remained subdued, the IMF
added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the IMF expressed its concerns over the setbacks
affecting the world economy.
</P>
<P>
The crisis in Brazil has imparted a new contractionary impulse
to the global economy while the financial sector fragilities in
several emerging market economies add to the risks of continued
turbulence, the IMF said.
</P>
<P>
In Russia, the delay in adopting coherent policies to promote
stabilization and reform has postponed improvements.
</P>
<P>
Japan's economy remains weak, and resumption of self-sustaining
growth is not yet clearly in sight, said the IMF, adding that
global trade imbalance may give rise to destabilizing movements in
exchange rates and may also increase protectionist pressures.
</P>
<P>
The IMF predicted that the growth rate for advanced countries
will be 2.0 percent in 1999 and for the developing countries 3.1
percent.
</P>
<P>
For the United States, the IMF predicted that its growth will
slow down from last year's 3.9 percent rate to 3.3 percent this
year.
</P>
<P>
Japan's economic growth rate will be minus 1.4 percent this
year, the IMF said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
