<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Scientists Invent Smart Antenna for Mobile Phone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Scientists in Britain's Surrey
University have invented a smart antenna which can boost mobile
phone's coverage and cut its radiation.
</P>
<P>
The antenna, developed by the university's Center for
Communication Systems Research, "could be in use by 2002 in the
next generation of mobile phones," Surrey University said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
The new invention consists of four antennas twisted around each
other to form a helix, together with some smart circuitry, which
senses the signals received and combines them for best results.
</P>
<P>
It permits reception inside buildings where signals are too
weak to be picked up by standard antennas.
</P>
<P>
In tests, the antenna was also found to reduce the power
necessary to achieve a given signal quality by approximately 10
times, depending on the configuration of buildings and trees
around the user.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the new invention, in the future global coverage can
be provided by both terrestrial and satellite mobile systems using
a single antenna, the researchers said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
