<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Trade Deficit Hits New High in February </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 20 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. trade deficit jumped
to a record 19.4 billion U.S. dollars in February as the global
financial crisis depressed U.S. exports for a fourth straight
month and booming consumer demand pushed imports to an all-time
high, the Commerce Department reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
February's deficit was 15.6 percent higher than the previous
record of 16.8 billion dollars set in January.
</P>
<P>
In February, U.S. exports edged down 0.6 percent to 76.6
billion dollars, led by a loss of 927 million dollars in sales of
commercial aircraft. Imports increased 2.3 percent to an all-time
high of 96 billion dollars as demand for foreign cars, clothing,
toys, televisions and stereos soared.
</P>
<P>
With back-to-back records, the trade deficit so far this year
is running at an annual rate of 215 billion dollars, far
surpassing last year's all-time high of 169 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Economists expect the U.S. trade deficit to continue rising as
long as the U.S. economy remains strong and many of America's
major export markets remain in recessions caused by the steep
plunge in financial markets that began in Asia in July 1997.
</P>
<P>
The country's trade deficit in goods area increased to a record
26.2 billion dollars, which was partly offset by the record
surplus of 6.7 billion dollars in services.
</P>
<P>
For February, the deficit with Japan shot up 13.1 percent to
5.3 billion dollars from 4.7 billion dollars in January, the
department said.
</P>
<P>
America's deficit with Mexico climbed to a record 1.8 billion
dollars in February as imports outpaced an increase in U.S.
exports to Mexico. The deficit with Canada fell to 2.4 billion
dollars from 2.5 billion dollars in January. The gap with Western
Europe rose to 2.2 billion dollars in February from 1.4 billion
dollars in the previous month.
</P>
<P>
U.S. surplus with South and Central America narrowed to 316
million dollars in February from 671 million dollars in January.
The U.S. exports to Brazil, which became the latest victim of the
global currency turmoil in January, dropped to 910 million dollars
in February, the lowest level since April 1996.
</P>
<P>
In addition to commercial aircraft, manufactured exports of
telecommunications equipment and electric generators also dropped
in February. Farm exports dropped 130 million dollars to 3.6
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the import side, foreign shipments of autos and automotive
parts rose to a record 14.6 billion dollars, up 710 million
dollars for the month. Other increases included computer
accessories, up 449 million dollars; clothing, up 202 million
dollars; toys, up 156 million dollars; and televisions and VCRs,
up 150 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
