<HEADLINE> Cyprus, Syria Combat Illegal Immigration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus and Syria have signed a
memorandum aimed at combating illegal immigration, Cypriot
Interior Minister Christodoulos Christodoulou said Tuesday on his
return from Syria.
</P>
<P>
Christodoulou said the Syrian government will take back Syrian
citizens who illegally arrive in Cypriot ports and illegal Syrian
workers who came to Cyprus in the capacity of tourists.
</P>
<P>
Damascus will also take back nationals of third countries, who
leave Syria's ports or airports and arrive in Cyprus illegally, or
whose last visas were issued by Syria.
</P>
<P>
Christodoulou said that all the circumstances apply to Cypriot
nationals who enter Syria illegally.
</P>
<P>
He said the Syrian government has provided that only
businessmen, people with scientific specializations, students and
Syrians belonging to high income groups will be allowed to visit
Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Christodoulou said that the work permits for some 1,500 Syrians
living in Cyprus had expired by the end of 1998 and dozens more
are estimated working illegally in the country.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the total number of illegal immigrants of
different nationalities in Cyprus, he said "they are estimated at
3,000 to 5,000." 
</P>
</TEXT>
