<HEADLINE> Kosovo Crisis Top on Agenda of NATO Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 20 (Xinhua) -- NATO's bombing in Yugoslavia
has changed the schedule of its summit which is due to be held
here this weekend and the crisis will be focused at the meeting,
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Albright told a special White House briefing that NATO's
bombing "will continue until this crisis ends on just and durable
terms."
</P>
<P>
She reiterated that Yugoslavia must stop military operations,
withdraw forces from Kosovo, allow all refugees to return and
permit the deployment of an international security presence.
</P>
<P>
As NATO's bombing failed after it lasted one month, the
summit to commemorate the alliance's 50th anniversary has been
clouded by the crisis.
</P>
<P>
However, Albright said that NATO leaders will talk about the
alliance's expansion and revise its strategic concept.
</P>
<P>
"The summit schedule includes consultations with the leaders of
those nations through the Euro-Atlantic Partnership Council. And
NATO will welcome new members and affirm that the door to the
alliance remains open," she added.
</P>
<P>
The leaders will announce a practical plan to help potential
new members meet NATO's high standards. The summit will be
attended by leaders from 19 NATO members and NATO's 25 so-called
partners.
</P>
<P>
NATO, or the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO), decided
to accept Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic last year. The
three countries will sign protocols to formally join the alliance.
</P>
<P>
"Our leaders will unveil a revised strategic concept for the
alliance and will take into account the new missions it may need
to undertake or, as in Kosovo and Bosnia, is already performing,"
she added.
</P>
<P>
"The summit will also commit NATO to developing military forces
that can perform the full spectrum of alliance missions, and we
will support the strengthening of the European pillar of our
alliance to help build a Europe more able to act effectively,
while maintaining its strong links to NATO," Albright said.
</P>
</TEXT>
