<HEADLINE> Sudan Affirms Reporters' Detention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Sudan's Ministry of Culture and
Information affirmed Tuesday the detention of three reporters last
week.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said in a statement that the three reporters were
detained under Sudan's national security law on charges of having
contacts with foreign intelligence agencies. The statement did not
mention any evidence on the charges.
</P>
<P>
Maha Hassan, editor of the Sudanese News Agency, and Abdul
Qadir, a correspondent for Saudi Arabia's Gizira newspaper, were
detained on Saturday and Sunday respectively.
</P>
<P>
A correspondent for the London-based Arabic language Sahrkel
Awsat newspaper was detained last Wednesday on charges of
espionage for Egypt, according his relatives.
</P>
<P>
Annour Ahmed, secretary general of the Press Association of
Sudan, has called for the release of the three reporters, saying
the association believes that detention can only be made under
established charges. 
