<DOCNO> XIE19990421.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EBRD Calls on East Europe to Speed up Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 20 (Xinhua) -- The European Bank for
Reconstruction and Development (EBRD) ended its eighth annual
meeting here on Tuesday with a call for Eastern Europe to
accelerate the pace of economic reform, despite the twin crises of
Russia and Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
EBRD President Horst Koehler told ministers and central bankers
there could be no turning back, saying "There must be no wavering
or backtracking in reforms and what is needed now is
acceleration."
</P>
<P>
Russia's financial meltdown pitched the region into an
unexpected economic decline last year with aggregate output in
the EBRD's 26 countries of operation sliding 1.3 percent. Now
conflict in Kosovo threatens to destabilize economies in the
Balkans and beyond.
</P>
<P>
"1999 will be a further difficult and challenging year,"
Koehler said in a closing statement.
</P>
<P>
Koehler said the bank remained committed to Russia but future
lending would depend on Moscow taking "decisive and credible
actions to take the reforms forward and improve the investment
climate".
</P>
<P>
Russian first Deputy Finance Minister and chief debt
negotiator, Mikhail Kasyanov, referring to the aftershocks of
Russia's financial collapse last August, said on Tuesday the
country would not be able to repay 1.6 billion U.S. dollars in
bond principal and interest due in May.
</P>
<P>
The non-payment raises the prospect of domino-style
cross-default on a program of 11 billion dollars of Russian
dollar-denominated debt.
</P>
<P>
"We are trying to find the way, the understanding with
creditors how to address this problem," Kasyanov said.
</P>
<P>
The Kosovo crisis overshadowed the meeting, with Albania
appealing for some 800 million dollars to cope with a tide of
refugees and other countries close to Yugoslavia hastily revising
downwards their growth projections.
</P>
<P>
Koehler said the EBRD was prepared to take on further projects
in the Balkans within the limits of its mandate. On the sidelines
of the annual meeting, international financial institutions
including the EBRD, IMF, World Bank and the U.S. Treasury met to
discuss ways to coordinate future Balkan aid. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
