<DOCNO> XIE19990421.0036 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Speaks Highly of China's Fiscal Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 20 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary
Fund (IMF) Tuesday spoke highly of the active fiscal policy taken
by the Chinese government in recent years.
</P>
<P>
"The fiscal stimulus supplied by the Chinese government last
year and this year has been very substantial," said Michael Mussa,
IMF Economic Counselor and Director of Research Department, at a
press conference in advance of the IMF annual Spring meetings.
</P>
<P>
He said because of its strong policy stimulus and significant
easing of monetary policy, China was able to sustain nearly
eight percent growth rate when the rest of Asia was encountering
"severe difficulties".
</P>
<P>
"That was very important positive contribution of Chinese
economic policy not only to China but also to avoiding a deep
downturn in the rest of Asia," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the reform process in China has not stopped by any
means and important steps have been taken to restructure the
banking system.
</P>
<P>
The IMF, in its latest World Economic Outlook (WEO), said
that growth appears to have been well-maintained in 1998 in
China, helped by large increases in public investment outlays
and cautious reductions in interest rates, but a moderate
further slowing is projected for 1999.
</P>
<P>
The current account remains in significant surplus, and
China's external vulnerability is limited also by its very large
foreign exchange reserves, moderate foreign debt, and
regulations of capital movements, said the IMF.
</P>
<P>
"These factors, together with the recent strengthening of
regional currencies, have helped maintain the stability of the
Renminbi against the U.S. dollar, and this is making an
important contribution to the restoration of financial stability
in the Asian region," it said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
