<HEADLINE> African Countries Urged to Move Faster to Solve </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Zambian President Frederick
Chiluba Tuesday urged the African countries to move faster to
solve the eight-month conflict in the Democratic Republic of Congo
(DRC).
</P>
<P>
Chiluba called for a quick process toward peace in the vast
central African country when meeting Albert Allen Peters, visiting
regional director for the United Nations High Commission for
Refugees (UNHCR ), at the State House.
</P>
<P>
The president said that African countries need to move faster
and find a lasting solution to the conflict because they have very
little resources.
</P>
<P>
Africa would gain nothing by prolonging the conflicts in the
continent, he pointed out, adding that Zambia appreciates the
efforts made by other countries to find a lasting solution to the
conflict in the DRC.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba noted that there is need for a coordinated approach so
that peace can be restored in the former Zaire.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed hope that a cease-fire would be signed soon.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Chiluba appealed for support from the international
community to help Zambia tackle the refugee problem.
</P>
<P>
He said that more than 20,000 refugees have flooded into
Zambia, fleeing the conflict in the DRC.
</P>
<P>
With Europe's involvement in Kosovo, very little attention
would be paid to the conflicts in Africa by the international
community, the Zambian president added.
</P>
<P>
Peters assured the president that the UNHCR would do everything
possible to help Zambia look after the refugees.
</P>
<P>
Peters also called for the resolving of conflicts in Africa if
the problem of refugees is to be eradicated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
