<DOCNO> XIE19990421.0039 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> War-Hit Balkan Nations Complain at EBRD </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 20 (Xinhua) -- The annual meeting of the European
Bank for Reconstruction and Development (EBRD) has heard a chorus
of Eastern European countries pleading for international help to
weather the fallout from the conflict in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The four-day meeting, which ended here on Tuesday, has been
overshadowed by the mounting cost of the Kosovo crisis on some of
Europe's most fragile economies.
</P>
<P>
Country after country came up with their different stories on
how hard the Kosovo crisis is biting in strained resources, lost
exports and faltering investment.
</P>
<P>
Neven Tomic, vice-chairman of Bosnia's Council of Ministers,
told bankers and potential investors the country was struggling to
cope with 40,000 refugees, sheltered in transit centres set up to
help resettle hundreds of thousands of displaced Bosnians.
</P>
<P>
"This year had been a year of return for our own refugees. Now
we have a new wave of refugees," he said. "We hope the
international community will support Bosnia and Herzegovina."
</P>
<P>
Tomic said it was too early to put hard figures on the economic
impact on Bosnia, but the balance of payments would certainly be
hard hit as exports to Yugoslavia were blocked.
</P>
<P>
Albania said it needed more than 800 million U.S. dollars to
cope with an estimated 365,000 refugees, who have swollen its
population by 10 to 15 percent. Economic growth was likely to slow
to five or six percent in 1999 against an original eight percent
target.
</P>
<P>
Macedonia, also flooded by refugees, said its mainly
agricultural exports were piling up unsold as the key transport
route across Yugoslavia was cut off.
</P>
<P>
Bulgarian Deputy Prime Minister Alexander Bozhkov said the
country was losing 1.0-1.5 million dollars a day in exports.
Foreign direct investment was likely to be less than half the $1.0
billion envisioned for 1999 and GDP growth would fall short of the
forecast of 3.7-4.0 percent.
</P>
<P>
Croatia's economy may shrink as much as one percent this year
as a result of the drop in tourism revenues, which could also
widen the current account deficit by 450-500 million dollars,
National Bank Governor Marko Skreb said.
</P>
<P>
Hungarian Finance Minister Zsigmond Jarai said growth in 1999
might fall below the government's four percent target if the
conflict persisted, although its impact was limited so far
</P>
<P>
Officials from the EBRD, the World Bank, the International
Monetary Fund, the International Finance Corp, the European
Commission, the U.S. Treasury, the European Investment Bank and
the Council of Europe's Social Development Fund met on Sunday on
the EBRD sidelines to swap notes on the region's likely needs,
according to a Reuters report.
</P>
<P>
EBRD President Horst Koehler said on Tuesday the bank was
preparing to join the international effort, drawing on its
experience with both infrastructure projects and small business.
</P>
<P>
"We already have some access to the region and some experience
there, and we do think this experience is helpful in this
particularly difficult situation," he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
But amid the calls for foreign aid, some countries showed how
outsiders can sometimes be more of a hindrance than a help. Tomic
said foreign-funded projects in Bosnia were grinding to a halt
because officials were cancelling flights to the country as a
result of NATO air strikes on Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
And Macedonia's ambassador to Britain, Stevo Crvenkovski, said
some aid agencies were flying in extra food for refugees while
local produce went to waste.
</P>
<P>
"We have an enormous surplus of food, yet sometimes Skopje
airport is virtually blocked by flights bringing in supplies," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
