<HEADLINE> U.N. Military Team to Escort S. Leone Rebel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 20 (Xinhua) -- A U.N. military team flew from
Freetown of Sierra Leone to Monrovia of Liberia Tuesday to escort
rebel leaders of Sierra Leone for peace talks, according to
reports reaching here.
</P>
<P>
The reports quoted a U.N. statement as saying that a 14-member
delegation of the rebel Revolutionary United Front (RUF) will be
travelling to Monrovia from Sierra Leone and as soon as they
arrive in Monrovia they would be put on board a U.N. aircraft and
flown off to Togo.
</P>
<P>
The rebel delegation was reported to include RUF battlefield
commander Sam Bockarie and Jonny Paul Koroma who led a military
junta which ruled the country from May 1997 to February 1998.
</P>
<P>
According to the U.N. statement, the Liberian government, which
has close ties with the Sierra Leone rebels, is providing an
escort for the RUF members from wherever they are arriving from
inside Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
The rebel leaders are due to meet their jailed leader, Foday
Sankoh who was flown from prison in Freetown to Togolese capital
Lome Sunday, for consultations intended to lead to peace talks
with the Sierra Leone government on ending the prolonged conflict
in the west African country.
</P>
<P>
The peace talks are expected to be held in Kara, the birth
place of President Gnassingbe Eyadema, current chairman of the
Economic Community of West African States (ECOWAS), who is to host
the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Sierra Leonean Attorney-General Solomon Berewa was quoted as
saying that the peace talks between the government and the rebels
will begin this week and the government is ready and waiting to go
to Togo.
</P>
<P>
Sierra Leonean President Tejan Kabbah came under pressure from
donors and regional allies to make peace after the RUF and its
allies invaded the capital of Freetown last January.
</P>
<P>
The need for peace talks became more urgent after Nigeria, the
backbone of the West African peace-keeping force of ECOMOG
supporting the Kabbah government, has already announced it would
withdraw its troops from Sierra Leone later this year.
</P>
<P>
In a separate development, Libyan Deputy Foreign Minister Ali
Triki has arrived in Togolese capital of Lome to take part in the
forthcoming peace talks to try to end the nine-year war in Sierra
Leone.
</P>
<P>
Liberian President Charles Taylor, a former rebel leader who
has historic links to both Libya and the Sierra Leone arrived on
Sunday in Libya which has close contacts with both sides in the
Sierra Leone conflict.
</P>
<P>
U.N. officials, Togolese government ministers and ECOWAS
chairman are currently engaged in intense negotiations in Lome to
bring the two sides in the civil war together. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
