<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Gives Alert on Israeli Flower Seeds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 20 (Xinhua) -- The Kenya Agricultural Research
Institute Tuesday issued an alert to flower growers over rose
stocks from Israel, saying that they may be infected with an agro
bacterium disease.
</P>
<P>
Director of the institute Cyrus Ndiritu confirmed that the
disease, which causes potato-like tumors on the roots and stems
which gradually strangle their output, has threatened to wipe out
flowers in about 20 local farms in east and central Kenya.
</P>
<P>
"Most of these rose stocks originated from Havered Beit Shearim
 Nurseries of Israel," said Ndiritu.
</P>
<P>
The financial damage is estimated at one billion shillings
(about 15.6 million U.S. dollars) in terms of investment in green
houses, chemicals, fertilizer, income from sales in Europe and
fees paid for the rose stocks.
</P>
<P>
Ndiritu warned that there could be more unsuspecting growers
who have had the disease introduced through continued imports of
the rose stocks.
</P>
<P>
The director revealed that the disease, which reduces the life
span of the infected roses from seven years to two, was first
detected in Kenya in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Flower exports earn Kenya over five billion shillings (about 78
million dollars) annually.
</P>
<P>
Statistics indicate that rose exports of the east African
country rose from 1,000 tons in 1990 to 18,000 tons in 1994
compared with its major rival Israel's slow climb from 19, 000 to
25,000 over the same period.
</P>
<P>
Kenya now is ranked the third in supply of roses to the Dutch
flower auctions, only after the Netherlands and Germany. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990421.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Official: NATO Bombing May Lead Confrontation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 20 (Xinhua) -- The NATO's bombing in
Yugoslavia could lead to a confrontation between the United States
and Russia, a Russian parliament official said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Alexei Arbatov, deputy head of the Russian parliament's defense
affairs committee said the conflict in the Balkans is the "worst,
most acute, dangerous crisis since the early 1960s" when the U.S.
and Russia involved missile crisis in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
The North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) holds 50th
anniversary celebrations this weekend in Washington. Moscow will
be unlikely to attend the meeting although it was invited.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the Atlantic Council, Arbatov said the longer NATO
continues bombing, the more pressure will mount on Russian
President Boris Yeltsin to intervene by providing arms and
volunteer fighters to Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
"If the bombing campaign continues, and if ground operations
start, then the flood of (Russian) volunteers to Yugoslavia to
fight would reach tens of thousands," Arbatov said.
</P>
<P>
"Fatalities would be horrifying, and Russia would be drawn into
war," he added.
</P>
<P>
The anti-NATO and anti-American sentiments have mounted in
Russia to unprecedented levels since the bombing began, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the allied bombing campaign has failed, but it has put
relations between Moscow and Washington into a deep freeze.
</P>
<P>
The bombing has killed the START II treaty, he said. "The
partnership between NATO and Russia is frozen, potential
cooperation on ballistic missile defenses is not a subject of
serious debate and willingness to cooperate on nonproliferation
(of mass-destruction weapons) is as low as it has ever been."
</P>
<P>
The Senate has ratified START II, a nuclear arms reduction
treaty, but the Russian Duma has delayed action repeatedly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990421.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Reserves "All Option" in the Kosovo Conflict - Solana </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 20 (Xinhua) - NATO Secretary-General Javier
Solana said on Tuesday that NATO reserved "all options" in the
Kosovo conflict.
</P>
<P>
He told Britain's Channel 4 television news that NATO would
leave open the option of sending a ground force into Kosovo if
NATO's airstrikes against Yugoslavia fail in its aim of forcing
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to bend down to the Western
alliance's demands.
</P>
<P>
"Of course we keep updated all the assessments we have for all
the good range of options that we may have. All options are open,
but at this point the strategy that we have is to maintain the air
campaign with determination," said the chief of NATO.
</P>
<P>
Solana said NATO's demands remained that Milosevic pull his
forces out of Kosovo and let in foreign troops to help ethnic
Albanian refugees return home and feel safe, and that agree to a
peace deal based on the Rambouillet accord he refused to sign.
</P>
<P>
More and more British politicians said in recent days that it
was impossible for Milosevic to sign on the Rambouillet agreement
and that NATO should stop bombing firstly to form a base for
political negotiation to end the Kosovo crisis.  
</P>
</TEXT>
