<DOCNO> XIE19990421.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Europe's Leading Markets Plunge as Wall St. Falls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON April 20 (Xinhua) - Plunging technology stocks on Wall
Street and an unexpected increase in UK inflation drove European
equity markets sharply lower on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The UK's FTSE 100 dropped 195.5 points or 3 percent to 6319.8
points, its biggest fall in percentage and point terms since
December 1, 1998.
</P>
<P>
Official data showing underlying inflation had jumped to 2.7
percent took many by surprise and also affected investors
sentiment in the market.
</P>
<P>
The FTSE index was dragged lower by losses in the heavyweight
bank, telecom, drug and oil sectors, with the likes of Glaxo
Wellcome, Lloyds TSB, British Telecom and BP Amoco all featuring
among the most notable decliners.
</P>
<P>
Electronic retailer Dixons was the worst performer in the FTSE,
losing 8.5 percent of the recent gains won on the back of its
Freeserve Internet service.
</P>
<P>
German benchmark Xetra Dax index closed down 2.87 percent, or
150.99 points, to 5101.41, while in floor trading the Dax dropped
2.5 percent to 5089.
</P>
<P>
Traders said shares had been falling in line with US markets.
Telecom and Internet related stocks were hit after the heavy fall
in US technology stocks on Monday.
</P>
<P>
French shares moved downwards in line with the rest of Europe.
The Cac-40 index of leading Paris shares closed down 2.9 percent,
or 126.07 points, at 4253, its lowest level since April 1. 
</P>
</TEXT>
