<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Budget Pushes UK Inflation Above Target </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Inflation in Britain rose above
the Government's target in March as the effects of the budget
kicked in, according to official figures released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Office for National Statistics said underlying inflation in
March was 2.7 percent compared to 2.4 percent the previous month,
breaching the Government's 2.5 percent target.
</P>
<P>
The rise, due to Budget increases in tobacco, petrol and
vehicle excise duties, had been expected and it is thought the
rate will fall back again next month.
</P>
<P>
However, it is believed here the rise could still deter the
Bank of England from cutting interest rates again from their
current level of 5.25 percent when it meets early next month.
</P>
<P>
Shadow Chancellor Francis Maude said: "These Budget tax rises
will mean that interest rates could now be higher for longer than
they would otherwise have been."
</P>
<P>
Some economic analysts said the underlying inflation in March
should not stop the Bank of England cutting interest rates one
more time.  
</P>
</TEXT>
