<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zou Jiahua Stresses Protection of Land Resources </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 21 (Xinhua) -- China must adopt a scientific and
economical policy to protect the land resources and ecological
environment, said Zou Jiahua, vice-chairman of the National
People's Congress Standing Committee, here before the World Earth
Day on April 22.
</P>
<P>
Zou told a symposium that the basic state policies of
population, resources and environment have great bearings on the
development of the nation.
</P>
<P>
China's world leading population, insufficient per capita
resources and deteriorating environment have become the pressing
issues restricting the social and economic developments, said Zou.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that the exploitation of natural resources should
be in a proper way, with the long-term interests taken into
consideration.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the state has required local governments to
protect the arable land, solve the problem of lack of water and
control environmental pollution.
</P>
<P>
The deterioration of environment must be basically controlled
by 2010, and the air quality in large cities must be greatly
improved, he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that geological disasters have brought large damages
to social and economic developments in some areas in recent years.
Efforts should be made to cut the losses resulted from geological
disasters by 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that more than half of the geological disasters
are the result of human activities. Scientific research and
technological development should be strengthened to protect the
geological environment, said Zou. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990421.0057 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cambodia Outlines Plan to Fight Food Insecurity, Malnutrition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Cambodian government outlined
its Action Plan Wednesday to fight the food insecurity and
malnutrition in Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
Cambodia held its first National Seminar on Food Security and
Nutrition on Tuesday and Wednesday to address the very crucial
issues facing the government and to draw up the plan to overcome
them.
</P>
<P>
The food security seminar, which concluded Wednesday with
recommendations for action, was presided over by Prime Minister
Hun Sen and attended by representatives from government
ministries, universities and some national and international
agencies, including the World Food Program and the United Nations
Children's Fund (UNICEF).
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen stressed at the seminar that it is the basic human
right to have enough food to eat.
</P>
<P>
"Despite a surplus in rice production over the past years, a
majority of the Cambodian people still faces food insecurity and
malnutrition," he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Recent studies revealed that nearly four out of ten Cambodians
are living below the poverty line and more than 55 percent of
Cambodian children under age five show signs of severe
malnutrition.
</P>
<P>
The causes of food insecurity and malnutrition are manifold,
but the most important causes in Cambodia, Hun Sen maintained,
were poverty and lack of purchasing power, rapid population
growth, insecure land title, low basic education and lack of
adequate health services.
</P>
<P>
In order to reduce poverty and improve the welfare of the
people, the government will give high priority to the development
of the agricultural sector as well as health and education
sectors.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen stressed that the development of the agricultural
sector will ensure food security and achieve growth in other
sectors.
</P>
<P>
The royal government has planed to invest 150 million U.S.
dollars in the agricultural sector in the next three years.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen said the government also planed to improve irrigation
systems, reform the land-titling system to give more families land
to farm and encourage small loans to help families start
businesses and increase their income.
</P>
<P>
In addition, he called for giving high priority to education
through propaganda to let families know that children need not
only rice and meat, but vegetables and a varied diet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
