<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bugalski Takes Catalunya Rally in Two-wheel Drive Car </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Philippe Bugalski of France with
his two-wheel drive Citroen won over the powerful four-wheel drive
machinery of his major rivals in the Catalunya Rally on Wednesday
in Lloret Dd Mar, Spain.
</P>
<P>
Bugalski's time was 31.8 seconds faster than his compatriot
Didier Auriol as he won two of the final three stages to take full
advantage of technical regulations which favored his car in the
event, reports said reaching here.
</P>
<P>
But Auriol was unhappy with the rules which helped Bugalski to
his victory.
</P>
<P>
"I am very happy for Philippe and for Citroen," Auriol was
quoted as saying. "However, the rules are not fair and should be
changed. It is not right that people who are committed to the
sport should be penalised by those who are not."
</P>
<P>
Citroen are not taking part in the manufacturers championship
and are selecting specific races in which to enter.
</P>
<P>
They cannot take points off their manufacturer rivals but their
drivers earn the points for whichever position they finish in, in
effect depriving Auriol of winner's points.
</P>
<P>
The regulations, which allowed Bugalski's car to be 270 kg
lighter than his rivals and gave him a power-to-weight advantage,
helped him become the first-ever F2 winner of a world championship
rally.
</P>
<P>
Auriol, in a Toyota, won the final stage of the third leg but
was unable to make any headway on the overnight leader.
</P>
<P>
Reigning champion Tommi Makinen, driving a Mitsubishi,
maintained his lead in the championship by claiming third place.
</P>
<P>
The Finn won two of the day's five stages to move up from fifth
position overnight to finish more than two minutes behind Bugalski.
He leads the championship by three points. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990421.0060 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore's First Educational Satellite Launched </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
SINGAPORE, April 21 (Xinhua) -- The first Singapore's satellite
for non-commercial purpose was launched in Baikonur, Kazhakstan,
at 11 a.m. local time Wednesday, Singapore media reported.
</P>
<P>
The satellite, codenamed as UoSAT-12 which will allow studies to
be done on wireless multi-media applications, was made by Nanyang
Technical University in collaboration with University Surrey of
the United Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
Signals transmitted from the satellite could be accepted through
satellite dish antennae on roof on one of the blocks of the
Nanyang Technical University and the system could be used for
educational purpose.
</P>
<P>
The satellite, made at a cost of 16 million Singapore dollars
(9.4 million U.S. dollars) was sent to its low earth orbit at an
altitude of 650 kilometers by a demilitarized SS-18 Russian
converted international ballistic missile.
</P>
<P>
The satellite, 350 kilograms in weight, was designed to
facilitate studies on wireless e-mailing, worldwide paging and
remote data collection in disaster monitoring and has a life span
of eight to 10 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
