<HEADLINE> Kuerten Moves to Third Round with Nice Form </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Brazil's Gustavo Kuerten showed the
champion form which made him French Open champion two years ago
after he entered the third round at the Monte Carlo Open on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The 13th seed beat Czech Bohdan Ulihrach 7-6, 6-2, 6-4 to set
up an all-Brazilian clash against Fernando Meligeni in the next
round, reports said.
</P>
<P>
Meligeni beat Briton Tim Henman on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Against Ulihrach, Kuerten was a little inconsistent, especially
in the first set tie-break which he lost 7-5, and at the end of
the third, when the Czech fought back from 4-2 down to level at 4-
4 before collapsing.
</P>
<P>
Playing indoors on the only roofed court at the Monte Carlo
Country Club, Swede Thomas Enqvist was again unable to make it to
the third round.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Open's losing finalist was crushed 6-2, 6-0 by
Spanish specialist Francisco Clavet.
</P>
<P>
But the loss was hardly a surprise as the 12th-seeded Swede had
never made it past the second round in five previous appearances
in Monte Carlo.
</P>
<P>
Morocco's Hicham Arazi, a French Open quarterfinalist in 1997
and last year, beat Argentine qualifier Mariano Puerta 6-1, 6-4.
