<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 15:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat Slams Netanyahu for Blocking Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat Wednesday slammed Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
for blocking the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu's failure to carry out the agreements signed with the
Palestinians drove the peace talks between the two sides to a
standstill, Arafat said at a press conference after meeting with
Arab League Secretary General Esmat Abdel-Meguid.
</P>
<P>
Israel shelved in December the Wye peace accord, signed last
October in Washington, after implementing the first of the
three-phased withdrawal from another 13 percent of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Arafat, who arrived here Tuesday evening after a tour to North
African Arab countries, stressed that realization of peace in the
Middle East is "an Israeli, Arab and international demand as much
as a Palestinian one."
</P>
<P>
He said that he will brief the Palestinian Central Council next
Tuesday on the outcome of his recent global tour aimed at drumming
up international support for a his plan to declare Palestinian
state.
</P>
<P>
Arafat insisted that he will declare an independent Palestinian
state on May 4 when the five-year interim period for Palestinian
autonomy under the 1993 Oslo Accord expires.
</P>
<P>
He has traveled to influential countries in the world to rally
support for his plan and their recognition for the future
Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
Many countries reportedly have advised him to postpone the date
of declaration in a bid to avoid complicating the peace process
before Israel's early elections on May 17.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian council will meet on April 27 to make a
decision on whether to declare a Palestinian state on May 4 as
long planned, Arafat said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
