<HEADLINE> Greeks Protest Against NATO Bombing Raids on Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Various groups of Greece Wednesday
staged anti-U.S. and anti-NATO marches around the country to
express their displeasure with NATO's airstrikes against
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
In Athens, hundreds of university students held a protest march
to the U.S. embassy and clashed with the police, who fired tear
gas and arrested two of them because they threw red paint, eggs
and planks of wood at the European Commission offices near the
embassy.
</P>
<P>
Dozens of members of the Association of Exiles and Detainees
marched to the U.S. embassy, shouting slogans against NATO's
bombing on Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, staff of an Athens hospital held a protest outside
the U.S. embassy.
</P>
<P>
In the northern Greek port city of Thessaloniki, some 30 youths
blocked the entrance to a downtown branch of the Citibank, holding
banners with slogans protesting against NATO's military actions
against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
In the southern Greek island of Crete, Hania Mayor Giorgos
Tzanakakis and the city council Tuesday passed a resolution
against the U.S. Naval base there.
</P>
<P>
Tensions in Hania have reportedly risen since the NATO bombings
on Yugoslavia started last month, and there have been protests in
the city and outside the U.S. base. 
</P>
</TEXT>
