<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angola Needs $500 mln to Restore War-Shattered </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, April 21 (Xinhua) --Angola needs at least 500 million
U.S. dollars to restore its power industry infrastructures ruined
in the civil war, a senior official has said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a meeting of the sub-committee of electricity of
the Southern African Development Community (SADC), Lius Filipe da
Silva, Minister of Energy, said that Angola is a country rich in
energy resources like water and oil, but the civil war has
destroyed most of the country's power facilities, with only 12
percent of its people have the access to electricity.
</P>
<P>
The average electricity consumption in the country is only
about 100 kwh per capita each year, only about one percent of its
hydro-power capacity, he said.
</P>
<P>
Silva urged SADC members to support Angola's legitimate
government to realize peace and stability in the southern African
country as soon as possible, saying that "any delay in the
development of my country would mean a delay in the region," the
Angola Daily reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The SADC electricity sub-committee meeting is focusing on
searching ways of cooperation to tap the potential of personnel,
technical and natural resources, so as to boost the economical
development in the region.  
</P>
</TEXT>
