<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Apache Helicopters Expected to Arrive in Tirana Wednesday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RINAS AIRPORT, Tirana, April 21 (Xinhua) -- About 24 U.S.
Apache helicopters are expected to arrive at Tirana's Rinas
Airport at around 15:00 local time (1300 GMT) Wednesday from NATO
bases in Italy.
</P>
<P>
Reporters were told by U.S. Air Force Public Affairs Officer 1
st Lt. Gina Jackson that "anyone interested in seeing the Apaches
can come by 3 p.m. We were told by the Army that something would
happen by then or soon after that," she told reporters gathering
at the gate of the airport waiting for permission to enter.
</P>
<P>
The runway, which had been occupied by helicopters engaging in
humanitarian operations over the past few days, has been cleared
and U.S. military photographers and video cameramen were waiting
as were reporters from around the world.
</P>
<P>
A U.S. military spokesman told reporters earlier Wednesday that
interviews might be conducted with Apache pilots, but they should
not be identified in any way for the sake of operational secrecy.
</P>
<P>
The heavily-armed helicopters are said to be one of the world's
effective weapons against armor.
</P>
<P>
The low-flying aircraft is being deployed to increase NATO's
ability to attack Yugoslav tanks in Kosovo which, along with other
parts of Yugoslavia, have been under attack by NATO since March 24.
</P>
<P>
The Pentagon said Monday that the helicopters, which are
vulnerable to anti-aircraft fire, would be operational in a week.
</P>
<P>
Over the past few weeks, the small airport in Tirana has been
equipped by the U.S. Army with lighting and an air traffic control
system for 24-hour operations.
</P>
<P>
A package of 2,500 U.S. troops, armored personnel carriers and
protective M39 ground-to-ground guided missiles and radar have
been installed at the air base.
</P>
<P>
Each Apache helicopter is armed with a 30 mm cannon, 70 mm
rockets and 16 Hellfire missiles.
</P>
<P>
The arrival of the Apache helicopters would mean the first
direct involvement of U.S. Army forces in the Allied Force
operation and a step many see moving closer to sending ground
forces into Kosovo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
