<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Boycotts NATO Birthday Celebration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Russia will shrug off NATO's 50th
birthday celebration this weekend in Washington due to the
alliance's airstrikes on Yugoslavia, President Boris Yeltsin
confirmed Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A foreign ministry statement said Yeltsin had decided Russia
could not be present at the gathering because of the "blatant
violation" of international charters perpetrated by NATO over
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
"President Boris Yeltsin decided Russian representatives would
not take part in the sessions of the Russia-NATO Joint Permanent
Council and the Euro-Atlantic Partnership Council convened for the
anniversary summit of NATO in Washington on April 23-25," the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
"The motives of this move are obvious. The military action of
NATO against a sovereign European nation -- Yugoslavia -- is a
blatant violation of the U.N. Charter" and other collective
security agreements, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Russia planned to attend the celebration a month ago, but the
alliance's bombing of Yugoslavia prompted Russian leaders to sever
ties with NATO.
</P>
<P>
"The military action of NATO has dealt a blow to the U.N.
system as a whole and to further cooperation in creating a new
collective security system in Europe," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"In these circumstances, Russia has no choice but to freeze
relations with the North Atlantic bloc. We have no other choice.
</P>
<P>
"We do not want to return to the times of the Cold War and do
not intend to get drawn into confrontation with the West. But
Russia will not encourage the arbitrariness of force by keeping
silent." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
