<DOCNO> XIE19990421.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kosovo Conflict Batters Romanian Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, April 21 (Xinhua) -- The Kosovo crisis has worsened
Romania's sluggish economy, which is a result of an international
embargo imposed on Yugoslavia years ago, the Rompres news agency
said Wednesday, citing a report by the Romanian Ministry of Trade
and Industry.
</P>
<P>
The Romanian metallurgical sector posted losses of about 30
million U.S. dollars, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
With a bilateral aviation collaboration program brought to a
halt, several Romanian firms have accrued losses of more than six
million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Volume of exports carried on the River Danube will decrease
by a monthly average of five million U.S. dollars. Further losses
will reportedly accrue after railroads take over the
transportation of commodities, another five million U.S. dollars
in all.
</P>
<P>
According the report, the consumer goods industry racked up 10
million dollars in losses after deliveries to Yugoslavia were
brought to a standstill.
</P>
<P>
Shipments of cement to Austria and Germany were also stopped,
and delay penalties have been claimed. Romania lost cash paid in
advance for commodities that cannot now be supplied, since its
Yugoslav producers were put out of business by NATO air raids.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the Romanian-Yugoslav trade figure in
1998 came third in Romania's overall commercial relations with
Central and Eastern states, outperformed by trade with Hungary and
the Republic of Moldova.
</P>
<P>
Profits from business with Yugoslavia in 1998 were in excess of
179 million dollars, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Common metals contributd 32 percent of Romania's exports to
Yugoslavia, mineral products 26 percent, vehicles and transport
equipment over 14 percent. Its imports from this country include
primarily mineral products, 41 percent; chemical products, 17
percent; transport equipment, 13 percent.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslav investments in Romania totaled 17 million U.S. dollars
at the end of 1998, five times more than that of the previous year.
The figure placed Yugoslavia in the 29th position among foreign
investors in Romania. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
