<DOCNO> XIE19990421.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Posts Higher-Than-Expected Deficit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 21 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines posted a budget
deficit of 33.463 billion pesos (836.6 million U.S. dollars) for
the first quarter 1999, 11 billion pesos (275 million U.S.
dollars) higher than programmed, a government report said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A report of the Bureau of Treasury (BT) said that for the first
three months this year, revenue collections amounted to only
105.122 billion pesos (2.63 billion U.S. dollars) as against
expenditures of 138.585 billion pesos (3.46 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Of the total revenues collection, the Bureau of Internal
Revenue collected 75.968 billion pesos (1.90 billion U.S. dollars)
while the Bureau of Customs collected 16.939 billion pesos (423.48
million U.S. dollars), the report said.
</P>
<P>
The BT contributed 4.927 billion pesos (123.18 million U.S.
dollars) to the revenue intake while other government agencies
brought in an additional 7.288 billion pesos (182.2 million U.S.
dollars), the report said.
</P>
<P>
Due to this revenue collection performance, the government
would be forced either to cut its expenditures or resort to
borrowings to finance the deficit, analysts here said.
</P>
<P>
If the government cuts its expenditures, however, its
pump-priming efforts would be curtailed, they said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
