<HEADLINE> GM Plans To Sell Opel Cars In China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 21 (Xinhua) -- The U.S.'s General Motors plans
to export some 2,300 Vectra cars from its German subsidiary Opel
this year.
</P>
<P>
The first shipment of the 1999 model Vectras already arrived in
Shanghai earlier this month. GM China announced here today that
the cars will be available in various parts of China soon.
</P>
<P>
The Vectras are aimed at the growing private automotive market
in China, a GM China sales manager says. He expects the cars to
become one of the most competitive brands of imported cars in
China this year.
</P>
<P>
GM already has a 1.5-billion-US-dollar joint venture plant in
Shanghai that produces Buick cars intended mainly for
institutional customers. In recent years, GM has been looking for
ways to start producing family cars in China.
</P>
<P>
The parts for the Vectra have been adapted to Chinese
conditions and emission controls. The cars were designed by Opel
and produced at an Opel plant in Hungary.
</P>
<P>
GM already showed the Vectra at China's annual international
automotive shows in 1997 and 1998. The Opel, GM's largest European
subsidiary, is one of the most popular cars in Europe.  
</P>
</TEXT>
