<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Envoy Reaches Consensus With Leaders of Three CIS Republics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Russia's envoy on the Kosovo crisis,
Viktor Chernomyrdin, said here Wednesday that he and the leaders
of three former Soviet Republics had achieved consensus on the
possibility of ending the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin, the former prime minister turned envoy, visited
Georgia, Azerbaijan and Ukraine on Tuesday and Wednesday in an
attempt to build support for Russia's position on Kosovo among the
three republics of the Commonwealth of Independent States. (CIS).
</P>
<P>
After talks with Georgian President Eduard Shevardnadze in
Tbilissi and Azerbaijan's Heydar Aliyev in Baku, Chernomyrdin
arrived in Kiev Tuesday and met with Ukrainian President Leonid
Kuchma twice to discuss the Yugoslav situation.
</P>
<P>
Before leaving Kiev for Moscow, Chernomyrdin told the press
that Russia and the three republics had achieved a unified
approach to the Kosovo conflict.
</P>
<P>
The positions of Ukraine, Azerbaijan and Georgia on a peaceful
settlement coincided, he said, noting that Yugoslavia is
unseparable and refugees must return home.
</P>
<P>
The situation in Yugoslavia has reached an impasse and the
Kosovo crisis may escalate at any time, he said, adding that this
could not be allowed to happen.
</P>
<P>
Calling on both conflicting parties to compromise, Chernomyrdin
also believed efforts should be made to prevent NATO ground troops
from entering Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin also stressed the danger brought about by
separatism. Separatism exists in some 100 countries in the world
and following separatism are wars, he said.
</P>
<P>
He believed mechanisms should be set up to curb the separatist
trend.
</P>
<P>
Ukrainian President Leonid Kuchma said his two meetings with
Chernomyrdin were "fruitful" and that the two sides will further
coordinate their political and diplomatic efforts concerning the
Kosovo issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
