<HEADLINE> Jordanian King Kicks off Historical Visit to Syria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian King Abdullah Bin
Hussein left Amman Wednesday for a two-day official visit to
Syria for talks with Syrian President Hafez al-Assad on bilateral
ties and the stalled Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Prior to Abdullah's departure, Jordanian Information Minister
Nasser Lawzi hailed the trip as a historical visit marking a new
phase in the Jordanian-Syrian relations in all fields.
</P>
<P>
The visit was aimed at further mending Jordan's ties with
Syria, which were strained by Jordan and Israel signed a peace
treaty in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Assad had been at odds with late Jordanian King Hussein over
the treaty until Hussein died of cancer on February 7.
</P>
<P>
However, Assad declared a three-day mourning for Hussein and
paid a visit in years to Amman to attend the funeral of Hussein
on February 8.
</P>
<P>
Assad's good-will gestures met with positive responses from
the Jordanian government, which has expressed support for
Syria's stands to resume peace talks with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Damascus insisted its peace talks with Israel, suspended since
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu came to power in 1996,
should be resumed from where it was suspended prior to 1996.
</P>
<P>
The Netanyahu government said the peace talks should be
restarted on fairly new grounds, a stance blamed by Syria as
unwilling to carry out the land-for-peace arrangements outlined
by the former Israeli Labor government.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah's visit to Syria was part of his regional tour in
April to rally support for the stagnant economy of his desert
kingdom and to coordinate Arab stands on the deadlocked Middle
East peace process.
</P>
<P>
The tour has already taken him to Saudi Arabia, Oman, the
United Arab Emirates and Libya. 
</P>
</TEXT>
