<HEADLINE> Zambia Sets New Strategies to Boost Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Zambia, which is expected to
become a major tourist destination in southern Africa, has drawn
up a five-year program to increase tourists arrivals.
</P>
<P>
Under the new marketing strategy which was issued earlier this
month, the country is expected to attract 660,000 tourists in 2004
from 362,000 in 1998, with an annual increase of 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
Cletus Chanda, marketing manager of Zambia National Tourist
Board, explained that the government is going to attract more
tourists with publicity programs on major tourist attractions so
as to improve Zambia's profile in this sector.
</P>
<P>
Chanda told Xinhua that his country have many favorable factors
to boost toursim, which include political stability, vast wild
life reserves and lodges, the prestigious Victoria Falls and the
friendly Zambian people.
</P>
<P>
The board has set up a web site to provide tourist information
of the country for foreign tourists, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the board will publish a tourist guide on
accommodation, attraction sites, pleasure resorts as well as the
general information about the Zambian people, their culture and
traditional ceremonies, Chanda said.
</P>
<P>
The Zambian national tourist administration would establish
closer relations with the media by inviting foreign journalists to
tour the country's major resorts.
</P>
<P>
"We are considering repositioning the Victoria Falls on the
international market. It is certainly one of Africa's best tourism
attractions and we can not just let its image remain as it is,"
Chanda said.
</P>
<P>
For a long time the Victoria falls in Livingstone, Southern
Province, has not been given the attention it deserves and that it
was high time a right picture was portrayed.
</P>
<P>
The government is projecting to earn 97 million U.S. Dollars
from tourism this year compared to last year when the country only
earned 74 million Dollars.
</P>
<P>
However, Opportunity Africa, produced in London by Charles
Barker publishing on behalf of the UK Department of Trade and
Industry, has indicated that Zambia's tourism earnings are
projected to reach 103 million dollars by 2000.  
</P>
</TEXT>
