<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Introduces Special Treasury Bills to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 21 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of Nigeria has
introduced the sale of Special Treasury Bills (STB) to banks for
the purpose of liquidity management in the country.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank which began selling the bills Monday explained
that the sale of the bill was due to the recent unprecedented
surge in base money which has seriously exacerbated the prevailing
liquidity overhung in the banking system, the Daily Times reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Following a recent government directive under which its
parastatals are now free to withdraw their money and lodge them in
commercial banks of their choice, the sum of 100 billion naira
(about 1.1 billion U.S. dollars) was withdrawn from the bank.
</P>
<P>
According to Vincent Omoike, director of banking operations of
the Central Bank, the introduction of the bills would assist the
monetary authorities in reducing the liquidity in the system to a
level consistent with the achievement of macro-economic stability.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the new arrangement shall entail the mandatory
sale of the Treasury Bills to banks which participate in the
foreign exchange market.
</P>
<P>
Under this initiative, explained the bank official, the
purchase of foreign exchange by banks shall be contingent on the
purchase of specified amounts of the Bills.
</P>
<P>
These bills, he said, shall not be eligible for discounting or
trading until after a minimum period of three months from the date
of purchase. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
