<HEADLINE> Singapore Provides Indonesia With Humanitarian Assistance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
SINGAPORE, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Singapore government Wednesday
released a statement announcing that the fourth phase of its
humanitarian assistance to Indonesia will be handed over to the
Indonesian government on April 22, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The shipment comprising 1000 metric tones of rice and a supply
of medicine will be presented by Singapore Ambassador to Indonesia
Edward Lee to Indonesian Coordinating Minister for People's
Welfare and Poverty Alleviation Haryono Suyono on behalf of their
own governments, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The statement also said this latest shipment of rice and
medicine is part of the 12-million-Singapore-dollar humanitarian
assistance package to Indonesia announced by the Singapore
government on July 6, 1998.
</P>
<P>
Half of the total rice shipment (i.e. some 500 metric tones)
will be distributed to the people in Jakarta through the Governor
of DKI Jakarta while the medicine will be distributed through the
Department of Health, the statement added.
</P>
<P>
Singapore presented the first three phases of its humanitarian
assistance to Indonesia in August and October of last year and in
January 1999, which comprised a total of 15,000 tones of rice and
three supplies of medicine. 
</P>
