<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Round of Price Cuts for Color TVs (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Shenzhen-based Konka Group,
China's major TV producer, today announced the introduction of a
sharp price cut in response to increasing challenges presented by
its chief rival, the Changhong Group.
</P>
<P>
Early this April, The Sichuan-based Changhong Group, China's
largest TV producer, slashed prices in early April to promote
sales, with the maximum reduction hitting 1,000 yuan (120 US
dollars).
</P>
<P>
Konka has responded by slashing prices by between 100 yuan and
1,500 yuan. The company held the largest market share in China's
large and medium-sized cities during 1998.
</P>
<P>
Konka General Manager Chen Weirong said the price cut will help
his Group accelerate the capital turnover rate and increase sales.
He said the resulting profit gap will be filled by raising prices
for hi-tech and patented products.
</P>
<P>
Chen added that price cuts will apply only to newly
manufactured units.
</P>
<P>
China witnessed a similar 1996 price cut initiated by the
Changhong Group. As a result, major domestic TV producers,
including Changhong, Konka and Panda, increased their market share
by a wide margin and substantially reduced the sales volume for
imported units.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990421.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Round of Price Cuts for Color TVs (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Tang Kaiguo, director of the Changhong Group's Beijing Branch,
said it is normal for TV producers to cut prices during sluggish
periods in order to increase sales.
</P>
<P>
He noted that 100 new TV brands were introduced last year alone.
Tang said Changhong will sharpen its competitiveness by focusing
on the development of hi-tech products and further increasing its
market share to resist cut-throat competition.
</P>
<P>
Various other domestic TV producers are also seeking effective
measures for ensuring their survival, with a number of related
ventures joining the price war by offering discounts.
</P>
<P>
TV sales for Beijing's large department stores have surged over
the past few days, with the daily sales volume for Changhong TVs
rising my almost 200 percent.
</P>
<P>
"Price competition is an important aspect of overall enterprise
competition and is quite simply a normal market phenomenon," said
Zheng Xinli, spokesman for the State Development Planning
Commission.
</P>
<P>
"The government hopes to avoid vicious competition and strongly
opposes sales of products at prices below the average level of
production costs," he added.
</P>
<P>
China's TV sales hit 21.6 million units during 1998, up 27
percent from 1997. Experts estimate that China's sales will
continue to grow at a double-digit rate annually over the next few
years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
