<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WTO Expects 1999 Export to Grow at Around 3.5 percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Export growth in 1999 is expected
to match that of 1998 at around 3.5 percent, the World Trade
Organization (WTO) predicted in its outlook for 1999.
</P>
<P>
However, the WTO stated that for the above projection to be
realized, trade growth will have to accelerate during the course
of 1999.
</P>
<P>
"This projection also assumes that slowing output growth in the
United States and Western Europe will be offset somewhat by
recovery in Asia," said the WTO in its latest report to be
published on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"A faster than expected slowdown in the United States or
Western Europe, or slower recovery in Asia, would clearly imply
export volume growth below 3.5 percent in 1999," the world trade
watchdog said.
</P>
<P>
In Indonesia, Malaysia, Philippines, South Korea and Thailand,
which were most immediately affected by financial crisis, the WTO
said, the sharp contraction of output and trade appears to have
bottomed out and a moderate recovery is likely in 1999.
</P>
<P>
According to the WTO report, the slowdown of world trade and
output growth had not been reversed by the end of 1998. "While
Japan's GDP continued to shrink in the fourth quarter of 1998 and
many West European countries recorded a weakening in their
economic performance, the U.S. economy accelerated," it said.
</P>
<P>
The WTO noted that significantly slower GDP growth in Brazil in
1998 and contraction in Russia will negatively affect the growth
of neighboring economies with whom they have extensive trade ties.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990421.0105 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Telecoms Sector Facing Fiercer Competition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 21 (Xinhua) -- China's telecommunications sector
is focusing on service to compete better with foreign companies in
the domestic market.
</P>
<P>
Beijing Telecom, a branch of China Telecom, announced today
that on May 1 it will cut the amount of time needed to get a
telephone installed or moved and it will try to response more
quickly to customer requests.
</P>
<P>
The deputy-director of Beijing Telecom, Jia Yong, says that
China's telecommunications sector is set to open to foreign
operators and that China Telecom's management which developed over
a long period of monopoly operations will not survive market
competition and needs to improve service and quality to keep its
customers.
</P>
<P>
China Telecom still has a monopoly in local telephones, but,
according to Beijing Telecom, the company has had an increasing
number of instances of failing to provide quality service and the
amount of compensation it has had to give customers has been
growing each year.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, the U.S.'s AT&AMP;T obtained approval for
Internet-related operations in China and, in response, Beijing
Telecom added new Internet services. It promises that customers
can get a dedicated line for data transmission within a month of
registering and can get dial-in Internet service within 48 hours
of making their first payment.
</P>
<P>
The company also promises to compensate customers if it fails
to meet the time limit.
</P>
<P>
Jia says that Chinese operators lag far behind foreign
operators in service. The average time it takes Chinese operator
to install a new telephone line is 20 days, but it's only 3-7 days
for foreign operators.
</P>
<P>
Some Chinese operators are trying to streamline management and
improve efficiency to reduce this gap and Beijing Telecom has
already laid off a number of employees who have not met efficiency
standards.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990421.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Sections of New Yangtze Bridge Join </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, April 21 (Xinhua) -- A new cable-stay bridge across
the Yangtze River in the lower reaches had its two sections
connected today near the city of Jiangyin in east China's Jiangsu
Province.
</P>
<P>
The Jiangyin Yangtze River Bridge is 3,071 meters long, with
the main arch spanning 1,385 meters. It is the longest in China
and the fourth longest in the world. It can allow 50,000-ton-
capacity vessels to pass.
</P>
<P>
The bridge is a key part of the intranational road project that
is expected to be completed by October 1, the 50th anniversary of
the founding of the People's Republic.
</P>
<P>
According to official figures, there are now 15 Yangtze River
bridges in commission, and six more, including the Jiangyin, under
construction, and 15 more being planned. 
</P>
</TEXT>
