<HEADLINE> Blair Says Hopes to Meet Russian Peace Envoy Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 21 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
said on Wednesday that he wanted Russia to play a part in
resolving the Kosovo crisis and hoped to meet Kremlin peace envoy
Viktor Chernomyrdin soon.
</P>
<P>
"The appointment of Mr. Chernomyrdin is a sign that Russia
wants to and can play a part in resolving this issue and I very
much hope he is able to play a part in this," a Reuters report
quoted Blair as saying in an interview to be broadcast later on
Wednesday with Russian NTV television.
</P>
<P>
"I would like to see Mr. Chernomyrdin as soon as possible,"
Blair said.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin, former Russian prime minister, was recently
appointed Kosovo peace envoy by President Boris Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
Blair said he believed Russia had a big part to play in Kosovo,
including talks on an international force to secure a peaceful
returning home for refugees.
</P>
<P>
"That is why we have all made such efforts to keep open the
lines of communication. Russia is a hugely respected country in
the world. We understand entirely its position in respect of this
conflict and we hope Russia can play a part in securing the basic
aim of justice for people in Kosovo," he said.
</P>
<P>
Russia has fiercely opposed NATO airstrikes against Yugoslavia.
</P>
