<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Official Says Chinese Businesses Should Bid More On U.N. Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 21 (Xinhua) -- A senior U.N. procurement officer
said here on Wednesday that Chinese businesses should participate
more in bidding on U.N. procurement jobs.
</P>
<P>
Martin Halland, vice-chairman of the U.N. Inter-Agency
Procurement Working Group, said at a meeting on "Doing Business
with the U.N. System" here that China can provide many products
and services because of their competitiveness. These include
foodstuff, textiles, farm machinery, and other basic products that
the U.N. needs both for development and humanitarian projects.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. buys over three billion U.S. dollars worth of products
and services each year. When government spending and loans from
international lending institutions are added, the value of
business opportunities in the U.N. system could approach 25
billion U.S. dollars annually, Halland says. But, developing
nations account for only about 40 percent of this.
</P>
<P>
U.N. got 15 million U.S. dollars worth of goods from China in
1996, and that grew to 34 million U.S. dollars worth in 1997. The
products were mostly foodstuff, contraceptives, water-supply
equipment, farm machinery, construction materials, and machine
tools and equipment.
</P>
<P>
Both the U.N. and China consider the figure too low, Halland
stressed and explained that one of the main reasons is that
Chinese businesses don't know the procurement market, but that new
technology, especially the Internet, could increase the
opportunities and give China a bigger share of the U.N. business.
</P>
<P>
This is a global market, he said, and it is necessary to be the
most competitive, but there are many suppliers in China that are
the best in the world, so they could win contracts with the U.N.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
