<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Higher Deficit Blocks Philippines Completing IMF Review </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Following the announcement of the
higher-than-expected budget deficit for the first quarter of the
year, the Philippines failed to complete its fourth IMF review,
government sources said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A shortfall in revenue collections has again caused the
government to incur a much higher budget deficit for the first
quarter of the year, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Finance Secretary Edgardo Espiritu was quoted as saying that
the Philippine penal has asked the International Monetary Fund
(IMF) to send another team in May to look over the revenue figures
once the April figures have been finalized.
</P>
<P>
The government incurred a budget deficit of 33.463 billion
pesos (836.6 million U.S. dollars) from January to March this
year, 11 billion pesos (275 million U.S. dollars) higher than
programmed, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
A visiting IMF review mission has expressed dismay at the low
revenue collection which has forced the government to cut down its
expenditure, part of the pump-priming program, they said.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine government would have to convince the IMF that
the excess deficit of 11 billion pesos could still be recovered
this year, they said.
</P>
<P>
The government is still sticking to its budget deficit target
this year of 68.4 billion pesos (1.71 billion U.S. dollars), the
sources said.
</P>
<P>
But in order to do so, the government may have to reduce its
pump-priming if it is not able to raise additional revenue, they
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
