<HEADLINE> NATO Preparing for Ground Operations in Kosovo: Albanian Newspaper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, April 21 (Xinhua) -- NATO has begun to deploy military
equipment in northern Albania along Yugoslavia's Kosovo province
border and is to soon start evacuating Kosovo refugees from that
area, reportedly in preparation for ground operations, the
Albanian newspaper Koha Jone said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper, the country's top daily, quoted "reliable
sources" with the Albanian Public Order Ministry as saying that
NATO deployed an unspecified number of anti-air missiles along
borders in Albania's Kukes and Tropoja districts in the past two
days.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, dozens of NATO tanks and armored vehicles, as well
as several hundred NATO troops, headed toward northern Albania
after being transported to Rinasi Airport in Tirana. At the same
time, the first group of NATO's Apache attack helicopters arrived
in Albania. They are stationed for the time being at Kucove
military base, 50 kilometers south of Tirana.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper said NATO has ordered the use of hundreds of
large military helicopters for the evacuation of Kosovo refugees
from Kukes to prepare for ground campaigns.
</P>
<P>
Local government official in Kukes Vladimir Shehu said the
district could only shelter 20,000 refugees at most. Reports say
that some 140,000 Kosovo refugees are now staying in Kukes.
</P>
