<HEADLINE> Anti-Taliban Alliance Claim to Capture Bamyan City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Afghanistan's Northern Alliance
Wednesday claimed to have captured Bamyan city, capital of central
Bamyan province, from the Taliban militia following fierce
overnight fighting.
</P>
<P>
The claim was denied by the Taliban militia.
</P>
<P>
Fighting for Bamyan has been intense in recent days with
hundreds of refugees fleeing the region for the safety of Kabul,
the Afghan capital.
</P>
<P>
"Our forces entered Bamyan from the south,'' said Abdullah, a
spokesman for the opposition.
</P>
<P>
Forces loyal to Hezb-e-Wahadat and Harrakat-i-Islami, two of
groups of the opposition alliance, launched their offensive late
on Tuesday night until they broke through Taliban defense lines
and into the city, he said.
</P>
<P>
Unconfirmed reports suggested that around 50 people from the
two sides were killed in the fighting.
</P>
<P>
So far about 100 Taliban soldiers were reported to be captured
by the opposition forces.
</P>
<P>
But Abdul Hai Muttmain, the Taliban spokesman, contacted in
southern Afghan city of Kandahar, denied losing the Shiite Muslim
dominated town.
</P>
<P>
Fighting is still going on in the districts of Daree Shekari
and Shashpool in Bamyan province, some 10 kilometers from the
city, Saad Mohseni from Harrakat-e-Islami said in his message from
Tashkent, capital of Uzbekistan.
</P>
<P>
Bamyan was the headquarters of the opposition alliance's Shiite
Muslim partner, Hezb-e-Wahadat, and was captured by the Taliban on
September 13 last year during their sweeping summer offensive.
</P>
<P>
Famous for the world's largest Buddhist there, the area is also
militarily strategic for the opposition because it enables them to
put increased pressure on the Taliban forces north and south of
Kabul.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban rule roughly 90 percent of Afghanistan, imposing a
harsh brand of Islamic, while the opposition, led by Ahmed Shah
Massood and former president Burhanuddin Rabbani rule the
remaining 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
Heavy fighting were reported in recent days also in Baghlan
province, Badakhshan province and Faryab province in northern
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations has been urging the warring factions to
renew peace efforts. However neither side appeared ready to
negotiate again. 
</P>
</TEXT>
