<HEADLINE> Many British Firms Apply for Queen's Awards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 21 (Xinhua) - Firms ranging from a manufacturer
of propellers to a maker of natural history films are among 101
British companies granted a prestigious Queen's Award here
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The recipients are from a wide spread of industrial and
commercial activity and size of company. Firms from Scotland,
Wales, Northern Ireland and all regions of England were
represented at the occasion.
</P>
<P>
However, the number of companies applying for the Queen's Award
for Export Achievement plunged to its lowest level in the awards'
33-year history.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, 1,300 British companies applied to win a Queen's Award
for exports. Last year the number fell to 864 and this year to
just 520.
</P>
<P>
Analysts interpreted this year's figures as graphic evidence of
the damage from the strong pound and last year's collapse in Asian
markets.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman from the Confederation of British Industry said: "
It is hardly surprising that the numbers are down, as exporters
have had a tough time."
</P>
<P>
"It shows the combined effects of the difficulties in South-
east Asia and Eastern Europe as well as the strength of sterling
throughout last year," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
