<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Love-the-Birds Week In Northern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The China Wildlife Conservation Association has joined wildlife
protection departments from Beijing and Shanxi, Henan, and Hebei
provinces for the activities, which will last until May. This
year's theme is "Let birds share the sky with people".
</P>
<P>
In Shanxi, 10 brown-eared pheasants that were raised in
captivity were released to the wild on April 13. China has 1,256
species of birds, 50 of which are either rare or unique to China.
</P>
<P>
With the increase in population size and economic development,
the birds' environment has deteriorated. In recent years, the
country has made an effort to protect the birds through rules and
regulations and by setting up nature reserves and increasing
afforestation.
</P>
<P>
There have been some good results in this. The number of brown-
eared pheasants has increased to more than 5,000 from some 2,000 a
decade ago. Recently, they were sighted in Shaanxi Province in
northwest China for the first time.  
</P>
</TEXT>
