<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southern African Customs Union Accord Unlikely </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, Aprilinue working beyond
April to iron out their differences.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted an unnamed official from the union as saying
Tuesday that much agreement had already been achieved on an
alternative formula of sharing customs revenue and on the
institutional framework to govern the accord.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of a revenue-sharing formula, "further work" was
needed on how to deal practically with the excise duties, he said.
</P>
<P>
Finding an acceptable formula has always been a sensitive issue
given the fact that South Africa's partners depend largely on
trade tax for government revenue.
</P>
<P>
The SACU comprises South Africa, Botswana, Namibia, Lesotho and
 Swaziland.
</P>
<P>
The official also said work had been done on the institutional
set-up that would manage the union's common external tariff
system.
</P>
<P>
The official, who said the talks on the institutional system
had reached a delicate stage, indicated that a report would soon
be drafted for consideration by ministers.
</P>
<P>
South Africa, which manages the union at present, is skeptical
of establishing a large and costly institutional dispensation,
whereas its partners want a more meaningful say in the running of
the new agreement.
</P>
<P>
The official said there was recognition of the need for a
broadly run customs union. However, this would have to be an
efficient union capable of delivery. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
