<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Easing Pain In China's Cancer Patients </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 21 (Xinhua) -- A new clause in China's clinical
use of morphine is expected to help provide relief to two million
cancer sufferers for their pain.
</P>
<P>
Drug Administration officials say that a new pharmacopoeia will
come out in 2000 with a clause on not restricting morphine dosages
for cancer patients, meaning that doctors can decide on the amount
of morphine needed for a particular patient.
</P>
<P>
The pain of cancer patients has been called a global problem by
the WHO (World Health Organization). Scientists say that the pain
puts patients in a depressed state, causing a large number of
treatments to fail.
</P>
<P>
Over 60 percent of China's 2 million-plus cancer patients
suffer from various degrees of pain and a third of them still get
no relief even on their deathbed.
</P>
<P>
China's old pharmacopoeia limited the dosage of morphine, But
Doctor Zhang Heping of the Chinese Academy of Medical Science's
Tumor Hospital points out that many sufferers need much more than
the limit to get relief from their pain.
</P>
<P>
The State Drug Administration allowed hospitals to disregard
the dosage limit in 1998, but, apart from Beijing's tumor
hospitals, it has not been applied in most Chinese hospitals.
</P>
<P>
A Drug Administration official says that many doctors and
patients are afraid of morphine addition but he points out that
few patients will become addicted and he adds that drug
administration departments have strict procedures for morphine
usage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990421.0136 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Plans to Develop Salt Industry, Boost Salt Export </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam has planned to develop its
salt industry and boost salt export, Vietnam's English daily
Vietnam News reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam's labor-intensive salt industry, the daily said, has
begun a plan to develop an export market within the next decade by
initially concentrating on quality and efficiency.
</P>
<P>
The plan includes building a salt economic zone in Ninh Thuan
Province, with intense investments in packaging and processing
technologies in order to considerably raise the price of salt.
</P>
<P>
The industry also intends to set up the processing of iodized
salt at locations in salt marshes throughout the country to
provide more employment for local people.
</P>
<P>
The industry expects to produce two million tons of salt
including 300,000 tons for export by 2010. 
</P>
</TEXT>
