<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Ranks 9th Among Leading Global Exporters in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, April 21 (Xinhua) -- China was the ninth biggest
exporter in world merchandise trade in 1998, up from the 10th in
1997, according to a list of leading exporters and importers
prepared by the World Trade Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
In 1998, China imported goods worth 183.8 billion U.S. dollars,
up one percent over 1997, said the WTO report, to be officially
released here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The top 10 exporters in world merchandise in 1998 were the
United States (683.0 billion dollars), Germany (539.7 billion),
Japan (388.0 billion), France (307.0 billion), the United Kingdom
(272.7 billion), Italy (240.9 billion), Canada (214.3 billion),
the Netherlands (198.2 billion), China (183.8 billion), and Hong
Kong, China (174.1 billion).
</P>
<P>
With imports worth 140.2 billion dollars, China ranked the 11th
among leading importers in world merchandise trade in 1998, up
from the 12th in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The top 10 importers in world merchandise in 1998 were the
United States (944.6 billion), Germany (466.6 billion), the United
Kingdom (316.1 billion), France (287.2 billion), Japan (280.5
billion), Italy (214.0 billion), Canada (205.0 billion), Hong Kong,
China (188.7 billion), the Netherlands (184.1 billion), and
Belgium-Luxembourg (158.8 billion).
</P>
<P>
In the world trade in commercial services in 1998, China ranked
the 15th in terms of exports worth 23 billion dollars and the 11th
in terms of imports worth 28.6 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The 10 leading exporters were the United States (233.6 billion),
the United Kingdom (99.5 billion), France (78.6 billion), Germany
(75.7 billion), Italy (70.1 billion), Japan (60.8 billion), the
Netherlands (48.3 billion), Spain (48.0 billion), Belgium-
Luxembourg (34.7 billion), and Hong Kong, China (34.2 billion).
</P>
<P>
The 10 leading importers were the United States (161.5 billion),
Germany (121.8 billion), Japan (109.5 billion), the United Kingdom
(76.1 billion), Italy (69.3 billion), France (62.8 billion), the
Netherlands (44.8 billion), Canada (34.8 billion), Belgium-
Luxembourg (33.6 billion), and Austria (28.7 billion). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
