<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> URGENT: China, U.S. Set to Resume WTO Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Chinese and U.S. negotiators are
set to resume talks on China's entry into the World Trade
Organization (WTO) on Thursday morning, according to the Ministry
of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation (MOFTEC).
</P>
<P>
Long Yongtu, MOFTEC's chief negotiator, is scheduled to hold
talks with U.S. Trade Representative Robert Cassidy. Long just
returned here this afternoon after accompanying Premier Zhu Rongji
on a two-week official visit to the United States and Canada.
</P>
<P>
Cassidy is expected to arrive in Beijing this evening and is
scheduled to stay in the Chinese capital until Sunday and possibly
longer depending progress made in negotiations, according to the U.
S. Embassy.
</P>
<P>
Topics scheduled for discussion include the legal terms for
China's entry into the WTO, tariffs on industrial goods and
further opening of the nation's service sector, mainly the finance,
insurance and telecommunications sectors.
</P>
<P>
"The fact that both sides are willing to resume negotiations is
a good sign," a MOFTEC spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
China's bid to enter the WTO and its predecessor has been under
discussion for the past 13 years. Premier Zhu's visit to the
United States earlier this month ended with important progress
made in Sino-U.S. negotiations on China's entry into the WTO. The
U.S. government voiced firm support for China entry into the WTO
in 1999.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton and Premier Zhu agreed that the two
sides should "intensify" negotiations for resolving remaining
issues in talks on China's accession to the WTO.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
