<HEADLINE> Israelis Mark Independence Day Amid Tight Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 21 (Xinhua) - The Israelis went to prayer
services, picnics, music and dances Wednesday to celebrate the
51st anniversary of the establishment of the Jewish state amid
tight security measures against possible terror attacks.
</P>
<P>
In a nationwide radio broadcast to mark the Independence Day,
President Ezer Weizman said he is full of hope and confidence that
Israel will reach peace with all its Arab neighbors in the coming
years.
</P>
<P>
Noting there has been a sharp decline in terror attacks against
Israelis in the last two years, Weizman praised the Palestinian
National Authority (PNA) for its actions on fighting terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Israel has to resume peace talks with the Palestinians quickly
no matter who will become the next prime minister, he
said. Israelis go to poll on May 17.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, citing alleged Palestinian
violations, has frozen the implementation of the Wye agreement he
signed with PNA Chairman Yasser Arafat last October.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli army has sealed off the West Bank and Gaza Strip
since Monday night, warning that terrorist groups might kidnap
soldiers or stage terror attacks during the holiday.
</P>
<P>
Heavy forces of police have been deployed in parks, shopping
malls and other "sensitive areas."
</P>
<P>
The State of Israel was proclaimed on May 14, 1948, but the
Independence Day was marked according to Jewish calendar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
