<HEADLINE> Blair to Urge Ground Assault in Kosovo: Newspaper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 21 (Xinhua) - British Prime Minister Tony Blair
has forged an outline agreement with key NATO partners to "impose
a solution" on Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic by sending
ground troops into Kosovo, the Guardian said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"Mr Blair will fly to Washington tonight in a determined effort
to persuade President Clinton that a ground assault can be
launched sooner rather than later," the British newspaper said in
its front-page report.
</P>
<P>
"Accompanied by General Sir Charles Guthrie, his chief of
defense staff, the prime minister will tell Mr Clinton that a move
to a ground offensive is the only credible option for NATO if the
alliance is to achieve its objectives within a timescale
acceptable to political and public opinion," said the report.
</P>
<P>
The Guardian said the three countries providing most of the
firepower in NATO's air campaign -- Britain, the United States and
France -- had accepted that "they should formally begin planning
the deployment of NATO ground troops before any settlement with
Belgrade."
</P>
<P>
Blair had decided to "put his personal prestige with Mr Clinton
on the line in an effort to strengthen the military assault on
Yugoslavia and to persuade him that Serb forces will have been
sufficiently 'degraded' that a land assault would not amount to a
full-scale war," the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
In recent days, Blair repeatedly ruled out the use of British
ground troops in the conflict with Yugoslavia, saying they would
be sent into Kosovo only as part of an agreed international
peacekeeping force and only when they are not opposed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
