<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Subsidence Reported in Xinjiang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Chinese environmentalists reported
today that extensive coal mining activities have caused varying
degrees of subsidence over a 10 sq.km. area in Urumqi, the capital
of northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Subsidence ranging from 1-3 centimeters deep and 10-50 meters
wide has affected approximately one sixth of Urumqi's total urban
area, according to Senior Engineer Sun Xiaoming, leader of a
recent subsidence survey team.
</P>
<P>
The most serious subsidence covers a belt over one kilometer
wide, according to comments Sun made during a Wednesday seminar
marking the World Earth Day.
</P>
<P>
He added that subsidence not only claimed the lives of 17 coal
miners in February 1995, but has also hindered normal industrial
and agricultural production.
</P>
<P>
Urumqi, the political, economic and cultural center in Xinjiang,
has a population of over 1.4 million. The city is located in the
heart of the Junggar Coal Field. The field has 10 billion tons of
verified coal reserves, with current annual production of some
three million tons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990421.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
