<HEADLINE> Warring Parties in E. Timor Sign Agreement to End Hostilities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Warring factions of the
pro-independence and pro-integration groups Wednesday signed an
agreement to end hostilities in Indonesia's troubled province of
East Timor, according to Antara News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The "Agreement to End Hostilities and Create Peace in East
Timor" was signed in Dili, capital of East Timor, by provincial
legislator Domingos MD Soares and commander of a pro-integration
group Joao Tavares, representing the pro-integration camp, and the
National Council of Resistance of East Timor leaders Leandro Isaak
and Manuel Carrascalao, representing the pro-independence camp.
</P>
<P>
The Armed Forces Chief Gen. Wiranto, who is also Defense
Minister, signed the agreement as a witness.
</P>
<P>
Wiranto expressed hope that the East Timorese could now live in
peace.
</P>
<P>
"I highly appreciate the (efforts of) people who have made
contributions to this agreement," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the East Timor issue is not only a national but an
international issue as well.
</P>
<P>
"I invite all parties to stop the fighting. We shall start a
new life by creating a secure situation for the people," he was
quoted by Antara News Agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
East Timor Governor Abilio Jose Osorio Soares welcomed the
signing of the agreement to cease all hostilities in the province.
</P>
<P>
"This (the signing of the agreement) is our wish. We have been
dreaming about this," Abilio said.
</P>
<P>
East Timor, with a population of some 800,000 and an area of
15,000 square kilometers, had been a Portuguese colony until 1975
and became an Indonesian province in 1976, but the U.N. never
recognized the move.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian government announced in January that it is ready
to release East Timor if the alternative to provide wider autonomy
is refused by the people in the region and the international
community.
</P>
<P>
Violence in the territory escalated early this month after
jailed East Timor pro-independence leader Xanana Gusmao made arms
call on April 5.
</P>
<P>
Last week, attacks by pro-integration militiamen claimed at
least 20 lives. The spate of violence has raised fears that it
would put the peaceful efforts in danger.
</P>
<P>
Indonesian Foreign Affairs Minister Ali Alatas would present
the government's final autonomy proposal during his two-day
meeting with his Portuguese counterpart Jaime Gama in New York on
April 22. 
</P>
</TEXT>
