<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Film Director Says No To Cannes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 21 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese director Zhang Yimou
has written to David Cronenberg, the president of the Cannes Film
Festival jury, to inform him that he has decided to withdraw his
two movies from this year's competition.
</P>
<P>
Zhang wrote to Beijing Youth Daily to say that he decided to
withdraw his two movies Not One Less and My Parents from the
festival because of the criteria but that he is "deeply sorry"
about it.
</P>
<P>
The president of the jury said in public that he dislikes
Zhang's two candidates because they are Chinese government
propaganda even though he did not deny their artistic value.
</P>
<P>
In his letter, Zhang explained that the theme of both movies is
love, a universal feeling, and that he could not understand their
being criticized for "political" reasons and that that is no doubt
a political or cultural prejudice.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Yimou is one of China's few world class directors and won
a Golden Palm Award at Cannes in 1995 for his movie To Live. He
has also won movie awards in Venice, Berlin, New York, and Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
What he can't accept, he says, is that Western critics have
long had 'political' readings of Chinese movies and stereotype
them as either 'anti-government' or 'government propaganda', which
is childish and one-dimensional.
</P>
<P>
He said he hopes to reduce this discrimination against Chinese
movies because it is unfair not only to him but to all Chinese
directors, including the new generation of directors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
