<HEADLINE> NATO Still Opposes Invasion of Kosovo: British Defense Secretary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 21 (Xinhua) - British Defense Secretary George
Robertson said on Wednesday that NATO still opposes an invasion of
Yugoslavia's Kosovo province.
</P>
<P>
"We still remain convinced that the arguments against a forced
invasion against Kosovo remain valid at the present moment,"
Robertson told the Sky television.
</P>
<P>
"But we are certainly looking, with all of our allies, at how
we are going to get the evicted people back, what numbers of
troops will be required to make sure that they can go back in
safety and security and that will certainly be one of the key
talking points at the NATO summit," said the defense secretary.
</P>
<P>
Robertson will fly to Washington Wednesday night with British
Prime Minister Tony Blair for a summit to mark NATO's 50th
founding anniversary.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday's edition of the Guardian newspaper said Blair had
forged an outline agreement to impose a solution on Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic by sending ground troops to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The Guardian said the three countries providing the
overwhelming firepower in NATO's air campaign in Yugoslavia --
Britain, the United States and France -- had accepted they should
formally begin planning for the deployment of NATO ground troops
ahead of any settlement with Belgrade. 
</P>
