<HEADLINE> Iraq Accuses U.S., Britain of Blocking Contracts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Iraq on Wednesday accused the
U.S. and Britain of blocking Iraq's contracts to buy oil spare
parts to upgrade its dilapidated oil facilities.
</P>
<P>
In a statement carried by the Iraqi News Agency, an Oil
Ministry spokesman reaffirmed "the U.S. and Britain have gone
further deep in their aggressive endeavor by depriving the Iraqi
oil sector of its basic and necessary needs for equipment."
</P>
<P>
U.S. and British delegates at the U.N. Sanctions Committee had
suspended a large number of Iraqi contracts without any
justification since the implementation of the fourth phase of the
oil-for-food program last June, said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The suspended contracts accounted for 79 percent of all the
contracts signed between foreign companies and Iraqi oil companies
located in the south of the country.
</P>
<P>
He said 24 and 17 contracts respectively pertaining to the
Southern Oil Refineries and South Oil Company had been suspended.
</P>
<P>
Since the fourth phase of the oil-for-food deal, Iraq has been
allowed to import 300 million U.S. dollar worth of oil spare parts
in six months to increase its oil production and export
capacities.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has long accused the U.S. and Britain of putting on hold
its contracts on purchasing oil spare parts under various flimsy
pretexts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
