<HEADLINE> Congo Rebel Leader Vows to Fight on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Jean Pierre Bemba, a rebel faction leader, said here Tuesday
that the agreement would not affect his fighting in the front, the
New Vision daily reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Both the rebels in the DRC and their main ally Rwanda played
down the agreement, saying any deal was meaningless without the
participation of the rebels.
</P>
<P>
Wamba dia Wamba, leader of the rebel Congolese Rally for
Democracy, reaffirmed their position that they want to talk
directly with Kabila before resolving the issue peacefully.
</P>
<P>
Bemba, who has been visiting senior officials here for a week,
said Uganda is trying to guarantee the security of its borders,
but he is "fighting against Kabila's dictatorship."
</P>
<P>
Uganda is the main backer of Bemba's rebel force, the Congolese
 Liberation Movement. Last year, Kampala gave Bemba military
training and has since provided his force with massive logistical
and military support.
</P>
<P>
A rebellion against Kabila in early August of 1998 has grown
into a regional war sucking in the armies of Angola, Zimbabwe,
Chad and Namibia on the side of Kabila's beleaguered government
forces.
</P>
<P>
The rebels, backed by Uganda and Rwanda, have demanded direct
talks with Kabila, a request which has never been satisfied.
</P>
<P>
The prolonged and expensive war forced Kabila, who has to pay
for the foreign troops fighting on his side, to seek to end the
armed conflict very soon.
</P>
<P>
Kabila's Information Minister Didier Mumengi said earlier that
the various factions in the conflict would meet in Rome from April
30 for talks mediated by Italy's Roman Catholic Sant'Egidio
Community. 
</P>
</TEXT>
