<DOCNO> XIE19990421.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK, Mainland Sign Aviation Meteorological Cooperation Document </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong and the mainland of
China signed a memorandum on long-term technical cooperation in
aviation meteorological services here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The document was inked by Lam Hung-kwan, director of the Hong
Kong Observatory (HKO), and Li Huibin, director of the
Meteorological Division of the Air Traffic Management Bureau (ATMB)
of the Civil Aviation Administration of China.
</P>
<P>
The cooperation covers a wide range of areas such as
meteorological communications, information exchanges,
meteorological instrumentation and personnel training.
</P>
<P>
On the exchange of meteorological information, the two sides
will hold regular discussions to explore new communication links
and to improve communication methods so as to increase the data
throughput and the types of information exchanged.
</P>
<P>
In this way, aviation forecasters and air traffic controllers
of both sides can have a better understanding of the weather
situation and provide better services to aircraft and airlines.
</P>
<P>
With respect to meteorological instrumentation, the two parties
will exchange technical information on meteorological equipment
which will facilitate improvement of the meteorological facilities
of airports in the mainland and in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with the memorandum, visits will be arranged more
frequently through which staff members of both places will learn
from each other in technology and operation.
</P>
<P>
Airports in Hong Kong, Guangzhou, Shenzhen and Zhuhai are near
to one another and the two sides agreed that the signing of the
memorandum will surely help promote the development of aviation
meteorological services, improve services and enhance aviation
safety and efficiency.
</P>
<P>
Lam said at the signing ceremony that it will lay a sound
foundation for further cooperation in future, adding that he has
full confidence in such cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Li said that owing to the proximity of airports in the Pearl
River estuary area and the overlap of their air spaces, there
should be close coordination of air traffic control among these
airports.
</P>
<P>
"Air traffic control will be more difficult during complicated
weather situations at all nearby airports and their air spaces.
The memorandum would help coordinate air traffic and thus enhance
flight safety and efficiency," he said.
</P>
<P>
Also present on the occasion were representatives from five
regional meteorological divisions under ATMB. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
