<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Depositors of Uganda's Closed Bank Not to Be Paid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Depositors of the Uganda's
Greenland Bank Limited, which was closed by Bank of Uganda on
April 1, will not be paid before June, when the bank audit is
expected to be completed.
</P>
<P>
This was revealed by Bank of Uganda Governor Charles Kigonyogo
when he met with the depositors's steering committee Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
According to a New Vision report Wednesday, the governor
promised that all bank depositors will be paid all their money,
adding that he could not, at present, give a specific date for the
repayment.
</P>
<P>
He described the Greenland Bank depositors as lucky because, he
asserted, depositors in Kenya and Tanzania and many other
countries could only get no more than the insured maximum if a
bank collapses.
</P>
<P>
Under the Financial Institutions Statute of 1993, only insured
deposits (a maximum of 30 percent) is supposed to be paid once a
bank closes.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of Uganda, the country's central bank, closed the
Greenland Bank for mismanagement and huge inside lending on April
1, just before the long Easter holiday.
</P>
<P>
The Greenland Bank has about 120,000 depositors. Both the Bank
of Uganda governor and President Yoweri Museveni have, on several
occasions, assured the depositors of the safety of their money.
</P>
<P>
The Greenland Bank is the fourth bank the Bank of Uganda closed
within seven months, sending another wave of panic among the
depositors and exposing more problems in the country's banking
sector.
</P>
<P>
There is now a loud outcry for the central bank to strictly
supervise the operations of commercial banks and to close them
before they become insolvent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990421.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain to Help Chinese Companies Gain Overseas Listings (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Lord Mayor of London Peter Levene
said here today that Great Britain plans to offer various forms of
assistance to help Chinese companies obtain overseas listings.
</P>
<P>
London, one of the world's major financial centers, is home to
numerous prestigious financial practitioners and well-established
institutions which are willing and able to help Chinese businesses
gain overseas listings, according to Levene, who is visiting China
as guest of the Beijing Municipal Government.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in an exclusive interview with Xinhua, Levene
expressed great appreciation for the Chinese government's decision
to ease controls on overseas listings for domestic companies.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that overseas listing will help China to draw
additional foreign funding.
</P>
<P>
"China's long-term economic development will require more
foreign capital," said Levene.
</P>
<P>
Zhou Zhengqing, chairman of the China Securities Regulatory
Commission (CSRC), met with Levene on Monday and stressed that any
Chinese company fulfilling requirements will receive approval to
seek listings on overseas stock markets. He noted that approvals
will be free of restrictions in terms of scale and number of
companies.
</P>
</TEXT>
