<HEADLINE> Britain to Help Chinese Companies Gain Overseas Listings (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Levene noted that many Chinese officials in charge of finance
and practitioners in the field are highly professional, and added
that their assistance and supervision will help Chinese
enterprises gain overseas listings.
</P>
<P>
However, he urged Chinese enterprises seeking overseas listings
to make ample preparations by acquainting themselves with rules
and regulations governing international securities markets.
</P>
<P>
Levene expressed understanding and support for the Chinese
government's policy of gradually opening financial and insurance
markets. He also noted the importance of the government's decision
to continue the opening effort.
</P>
<P>
The Lord Mayor of London voiced pleasure at seeing the sound
development of Sino-British relations in recent years, and noted
that last year's exchange of visits by Prime Minister Tony Blair
and Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji strengthened bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, he said, sound bilateral ties have provided a solid
foundation for exchanges and cooperation in the trade, economic
and financial sectors, said Levene.
</P>
<P>
Levene recounted his visit to Beijing three years ago at a time
when many British insurance companies were attempting to gain
operating licenses in China. He also expressed great pleasure that
two British companies have since succeeded in their efforts.
</P>
<P>
Sixteen foreign insurance companies have received approval to
operate in China, including the Royal Sun Alliance Insurance Group
and Prudential Corporation.
</P>
<P>
The city of London, Britain's major financial and business
center, is home to the headquarters operations of several nations'
largest banks and insurance companies. A total of 540 foreign
banks, including the Bank of China, have established branches in
the city. 
