<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Consumer Credit Expected To Breathe Life Into China's Markets (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Li Zhengshu, a Beijing factory
worker, bought a color TV, a refrigerator, a washing machine, an
air conditioner, and electric appliances worth more than 50,000
yuan (some 6,000 U.S. dollars), by making a 20,000-yuan down
payment at Parkson Shopping Center.
</P>
<P>
Li was one of the first Chinese to benefit from the consumer
credit business launched by Chinese banks in early March. Beijing
Commercial Bank paid off the rest of the 30,000 yuan that Li owed
and she will make monthly payments to the bank on the principal
and interest.
</P>
<P>
In early March, the People's Bank of China (PBOC), China's
central bank, gave the go-ahead to commercial banks on consumer
credit and issued guidelines on the business. A PBOC spokesman
says that this will help promote consumer spending, boost market
demand, and push forward the steady development of the nation's
economy.
</P>
<P>
Commercial banks can help businesses and housing and motor
vehicle purchases. The central bank's decision has been met with
enthusiasm by commercial banks, which have opened credit lines for
motor vehicle, housing, and consumer goods purchases and even for
weddings, college tuition, and tourism.
</P>
<P>
The loans range in size from 2,000 yuan to as much as 100,000
yuan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
