<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China To Increase Housing Sales Through Financial Restructuring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 21 (Xinhua) -- China is trying to commercialize
the housing business by setting up banks, funds, loans, and
mortgages for the purpose.
</P>
<P>
According to Xie Jiajing, a senior Construction Ministry
official, China is still suffering from slack housing sales, with
50 million sq.m. of housing lying idle, and the lack of ability to
purchase housing and the high housing prices account for it.
</P>
<P>
So, to promote the housing business and carry out the new
housing reforms, finance departments have already reduced the
number of unreasonable taxes in housing construction and sales and
the country is setting up banks on a trial basis in a number of
cities that are expected to provide financial guarantees, loans,
and mortgages.
</P>
<P>
Public housing funds now exceed 130 billion yuan and Shanghai,
which was the first city to introduce a public housing fund, has
15 billion yuan in public housing fund. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990421.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1st Quarter Quiet for Industrial Action in S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 21 (Xinhua) -- The loss of 25,000 man-days
to strikes in the first quarter of the year was the lowest in the
past eight years in South Africa, The Citizen daily Wednesday
quoted a labor relations consultancy official as saying.
</P>
<P>
Compared to 288,000 man-days lost to industrial action in the
first quarter of 1998, 78,000 in 1997, and 175,000 in 1996, the
first quarter of this year could be considered quiet.
</P>
<P>
However, increased industrial action is expected later this
year as the bulk of wage negotiations began in the second half, an
official from Andrew Levy and Associates said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"As this will coincide with the election period, it may have
the effect of raising worker expectations," said the official.
</P>
<P>
It anticipated that wages would again form the major strike
trigger in 1999.
</P>
<P>
"There is additional pressure on wage earners as formal sector
job losses continue at alarming rates and inflation and high
interest rates erode workers' purchasing power.
</P>
<P>
"Employers, on the other hand, are expected to push for lower
(wage) increases based on trading figures for the previous 12
months.
</P>
<P>
"This scenario is likely to produce some hard bargaining during
1999 which will test the resolve of both sides," the official
said.
</P>
<P>
Wage settlements had continued to fall, from an average
increase of 8.6 percent in 1998 to eight percent in March this
year.
</P>
<P>
With inflation expected to average between seven and eight
percent this year, wage settlements are expected to fall within
this range this year, it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990421.0188 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Consumer Credit Expected to Breathe Life into China's Markets (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The new decision has been embraced by consumers as well. In the
past month, department stores in Beijing, Tianjin, Shanghai and
other big cities have seen a surge in the credit business.
</P>
<P>
Sources at China Industrial and Commercial Bank (CICB) say that
in Tianjin and Shanghai the bank handled more than 600 consumer
credit deals worth more than 7 million yuan in one month.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say that when the credit business is fully developed
it will be a powerful force in the nation's economy. But, they add,
because of the Chinese tendency to save money, it will take time
to get them to change their traditional ways and spend more.
</P>
<P>
Professor Xiao Zhuoji of Beijing University says that, based on
international experience, consumer credit business is a
significant step in stimulating consumer spending, improving
banks' credit structure, and holding financial risks to a minimum.
</P>
<P>
He says that the most pressing problem now is to cultivate more
open mentality among consumers, and come up with credit-oriented
policies and systems.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say that a credit system should be established as
early as possible, with credit records, credit appraisals, and
credit risk controls.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Wang Wei of the State Council's Development and Research
Center says that banks should use bank cards more fully to develop
consumer credit. China's commercial banks have issued more than 50
million credit cards and the card holders are an important part of
the business.
</P>
<P>
The success in the credit business has encouraged commercial
banks, which have announced plans to expand the business. CICB has
extended its consumer credit business to 41 large and medium-sized
cities, and the Bank of China plans to make consumer credit
account for 10 percent of its new loans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
