<DOCNO> XIE19990421.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 09:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Slams British-Dutch Draft Resolution on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, April 21 (Xinhua) -- An Iraqi daily on Wednesday
lashed out at the British-Dutch draft resolution to the U.N.
Security Council on the Iraqi issue, describing it as very bad and
aims at restricting its hands.
</P>
<P>
Al-Thawra daily, organ of the Arab Baath Socialist Party, said
in an article that Iraq had repeatedly confirmed that lifting the
embargo was a legal right and it was not a gift or reward from the
Security Council.
</P>
<P>
Britain and Netherlands proposed last Friday to abolish the
U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) in charge of dismantling Iraq's
weapons of mass destruction with an enlarged body to carry out
more intrusive inspections of Iraq's banned weapons.
</P>
<P>
They also proposed to ease sanctions against Iraq, including
lifting the ceiling by which Iraq could sell its oil to buy food,
medicines and other necessities for its people.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper article said that Paragraph 22 of the Security
Council resolution 687 is very clear and it binds the Council to
fulfil its reciprocal obligations vis-a-vis Iraq by lifting the
embargo since Iraq had honored all its commitments.
</P>
<P>
It stressed that any new draft designed to delay the lifting of
embargo off Iraq was unacceptable and futile.
</P>
<P>
"Any party that wants positive and constructive relations
between Iraq and the Security Council should be aware that the
Council must fulfil its obligations toward Iraq..." said the
article.
</P>
<P>
Russia last Friday also proposed a new plan to the Council in a
bid to break the Council's impasse on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
In its plan, Russia recommended to lift all the economic
sanctions against Iraq except an arms embargo in stages.
</P>
<P>
U.N. weapons inspections in Iraq have been suspended since last
December's U.S.-British airstrikes on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has ever since announced that UNSCOM is dead and it will
not allow weapons inspections to resume. Instead, Iraq demands the
U.N. to lift the nine-year sanctions imposed on it following its
1990 invasion of Kuwait. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
