<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 09:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian Conservatives to Impeach Culture Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 21 (Xinhua) -- A group of 31 Iranian
conservative Majlis (parliament) deputies on Wednesday submitted
an impeachment motion on the moderate Minister of Culture and
Islamic Guidance Ataollah Mohajerani.
</P>
<P>
The motion was read out at the end of the Majlis open session
Wednesday morning, the Islamic Republic News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The move came after the conservatives lodged sharp attacks on
Mohajerani's policy on press freedom, which was advocated by
President Mohammad Khatami during his presidential elections
campaign.
</P>
<P>
Mohajerani is the second minister of Khatami's cabinet who was
targeted by the powerful conservatives, which still dominate the
country's most important organs, such as the judiciary, the
parliament and the armed forces.
</P>
<P>
Last June, former Interior Minister Abdollah Nouri, another
close ally of President Khatami, was impeached by the Majlis on
charge of "creating tensions in the society, issuing provocative
statements and using inexperienced persons for the managerial
posts at the interior ministry."
</P>
<P>
Under the Majlis regulations, Mohajerani should appear before
the Majlis within 10 days to explain himself after the proposed
impeachment motion was presented.
</P>
<P>
Rumors on Mohajerani's possible impeachment have been widely
spreading since the Iranian new year (started on March 21). And many
moderate figures have warned that the conservatives have planned a
series of offensives to elbow the moderates out of the Iranian
political arena. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
