<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0730 GMT April 21 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- As many as 25 people were killed Tuesday as two
heavily armed young men opened fire at a high school southwest of
Denver, capital of the Colorado State of the United States.
</P>
<P>
The gunmen, believed to be former students at Columbine High
School, were found dead at the library after the shooting. They,
wearing black trench coats and masks, moved calmly through the
school library and giggled as they shot at students at lunch time.
Some witnesses said the gunmen, armed with automatic weapons and
explosives, appeared to have two particular targets -- minority
students and popular athletes, apparently taking revenge at the
school with 1,800 students. (US-School-Shooting)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- A senior Yugoslav diplomat Tuesday called on
the international community to help bring an end to the ongoing
NATO bombing in order to restore peace and security in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview with Xinhua, Vladislav Jovanovic,
charge d'affaires of the Yugoslav Mission to the United Nations,
said that NATO, by bombing Yugoslavia, has challenged the
authority of the United Nations and the norm of international law.
Under the UN Charter, any military action against a sovereign and
independent country should first seek the approval of the UN
Security Council, which has the primary responsibility for the
maintenance of peace and security in the world. (UN-Yugoslavia-
Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BELGRADE -- NATO jets early Wednesday bombed the Belgrade
headquarters of Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic's ruling
Socialist Party and left the high-rise building in flames.
</P>
<P>
Belgrade's civil defense chief Gragan Covic told a local
television station after the attack that the raid "certainly
caused casualties." Several missiles hit the building, known as
the Business Center Usce, at 03:15 a.m. local time. The building
is located in the heart of Novi Belgrade, just opposite the Hyatt
hotel where many foreign reporters stay. (NATO-Belgrade-Bobming)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BUCHAREST -- Romania's largest opposition party, the Social
Democratic Party (SDP), said Tuesday it opposes giving NATO "
unlimited" access to Romania's sky, noting NATO's military action
on Yugoslavia has worsened the tragic situation there.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued after a meeting between SDP Chairman Ion
Iliescu, also former Romanian president, and President Emil
Constantinescu, the party said the Romanian parliament had already
clarified Romania's principled stand on the Kosovo crisis in a
resolution on March 30, in which Romania recognizes Yugoslavia's
territorial integrity and sovereignty and appeals for respect for
the legitimate rights of the ethnic Albanians in Kosovo. It noted
that under an agreement reached last October, Romania permits NATO
airplanes to enter its sky only under "urgent and unexpected
circumstances." The agreement is still effective and any new
decision on this matter by the authority should not go beyond it,
it added. (Romania-NATO-Opposition) 
</P>
</TEXT>
