<HEADLINE> Illegal Immigrants in Cyprus Jail on Hunger Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Sixteen detainees in Cyprus'
southern Larnaca town Tuesday went on a hunger strike to protest
against their continued detention for illegal immigration, the
Cyprus Mail newspaper reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Larnaca Police Chief Savvas Lardis and UNHCR Head of Liaison
Office Sharon Bernard confirmed the report.
</P>
<P>
The hunger-strikers say they are tired of being held as common
criminals without being convicted of any offense.
</P>
<P>
One of the detainees, who identified himself only as Siraf,
said, "We need a solution."
</P>
<P>
Bernard confirmed that Siraf had tried to commit suicide and he
was receiving psychiatric consulting in jail.
</P>
<P>
Reports say there are 24 alleged illegal immigrants under
virtual house arrest in a hotel in the southwestern Limassol town
since last June.
</P>
<P>
They were among the 113 illegal migrants rescued from a leaky
fishing boat in Cyprus waters last year. Most of them have been
deported.
</P>
<P>
Another 68 are being held on the British Base in Cyprus,
following their landing on the shores of the Base last autumn.
</P>
