<HEADLINE> US Wholesaler Looking To Expand Operations In China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
BEIJING, April 21 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. wholesale chain Costco is
hoping to get licensed to expand its operations in China.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting with Chinese State Councilor Wu Yi here this
morning, James Dennis Sinegal, the CEO of Costco, said he expects
to get Costco operating in China as soon as possible. He is in
Beijing with a delegation of senior Costco officials to push for
greater cooperation with their Chinese partner Normart, a retail
company.
</P>
<P>
Wu told Sinegal that China is opening up its retail sector
gradually, but said she welcomes Costco and that their application
has been submitted to the State Council for final approval. The
Chinese government has approved a total of 20 joint retail-sales
ventures.
</P>
<P>
Sinegal said that Costco is ready to establish long-term
cooperative relations with China and pledged to share management
ideas with the Chinese partners and to help train personnel.
Costco will also consider exporting more Chinese products to other
countries through its global warehouse network.
</P>
<P>
He told Xinhua that the group will go to Japan for an opening
ceremony for a new Costco warehouse. The company has nearly 300
warehouses in the United States, Canada, Britain, Mexico, Japan,
the Republic of Korea (ROK), and Taiwan, with total annual sales
of 26 billion U.S. dollars last year. 
</P>
