<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 07:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Agrees to Provide Jordan with Full </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Jordan and Israel have solved a
water dispute after Israel promised to provide Jordan with full
water share as stipulated in the 1994 peace treaty, the
semi-official Jordan Times reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Jordan and Israel, during a joint water committee meeting last
week, reached an agreement under which Jordan will receive 55
million cubic meters of water from the Jewish state in 1999, the
paper said.
</P>
<P>
The new arrangement is a solution to the water dispute between
the two countries which erupted last month when Israel proposed to
cut its water supplies to Jordan by over 40 percent this summer
due to a severe drought that hit both countries.
</P>
<P>
Jordan lodged a strong protest against the Israeli proposal to
cut water supplies, and stressed the water clauses were the key
elements in the 1994 peace treaty between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The water dispute posed a most serious threat to
Jordanian-Israeli ties in years, and more than 15 Jordanian
parliamentarians proposed to scrap the whole peace treaty if
Israel failed to carry out its water clauses.
</P>
<P>
Jordan has a Mediterranean weather and relies mainly on
rainwater to meet its water needs in winter, but will depend
largely on water supplies from Israel in summer when it has fewer
raindrops.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1999, Jordan needs some 283 million cubic
meters of water to meet its domestic demands, but its water
capacity only provides 254 million cubic meters, or a 10
percent deficit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990421.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
