<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Experts Cite Importance of Nutritious Breakfast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Nutritionists are urging most
Chinese to change their diets and suggest that the breakfast menu
should include milk and eggs rather than junk foods.
</P>
<P>
The fact that a large number of Chinese citizens pay little
attention to breakfast has resulted in increasing malnutrition in
spite of comparatively high living standards, according to experts.
</P>
<P>
Many Chinese people consume an adequate level of calories, but
nonetheless fall short in terms of nutrition. Therefore, milk and
eggs are a good choice for breakfast.
</P>
<P>
Song Chungang, chairman of the Dairy Industry Association,
noted that the average per capita consumption of milk in China
stands at only 6.6 kg, far short of the worldwide average was 102
kg and the 300 kg level in developed countries 300 kg.
</P>
<P>
The average cost for a bottle of milk stands at one yuan, with
one kilogram eggs costing six yuan, according to Song.
</P>
<P>
Jiang Jianping, deputy director of the National Food and
Nutrition Council, recently suggested the initiation of a
nationwide campaign to increase the milk intake for children who
run the risk of contracting diseases related to insufficient
consumption of dairy products.
</P>
<P>
Recent surveys show that a large number of Chinese children
suffer from rickets and osteoporosis due to inadequate milk
consumption.
</P>
<P>
A nationwide campaign launched in 1996 to promote the
consumption of soybean milk has proved highly effective. The
Ministry of Agriculture, the State Administration of Light
Industry and ministries of Education and Health have also launched
related programs.
</P>
<P>
The incidence rate of anemia for male and female students
attending 22 schools in 10 provinces dropped by 7.9 and 8.5
percentage points respectively following the introduction of
soybean milk as a regular breakfast item, said Jiang. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990421.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand PM Urges Prudent Use of Natural Resources </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, April 21 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand Prime Minister
Jenny
Shipley Wednesday called for using natural resources in "a prudent
and
sustainable manner."
</P>
<P>
While signing a UNESCO (United Nations Educational, Scientific
and
Cultural Organization) Oceans Charter at the parliament building
here
Wednesday, Shipley said New Zealand already has the fourth largest

exclusive economic zone in the world which covers about 4 million
square
kilometers of ocean.
</P>
<P>
"This could be extended by a further 2.4 million square
kilometers,
giving us access to resources that could be worth trillions of
dollars,"
she said.
</P>
<P>
Under the United Nations Convention on the Law of the Sea, New

Zealand has until 2006 to claim an extension of the ocean floor
under its
jurisdiction. The extension will mean more than 6 million square
kilometers of ocean floor or about 1 percent of the earth's
surface would
come under New Zealand's control.
</P>
<P>
The stuff below the sea holds "an enormous amount of wealth
that will
be the new economic frontier of the future," Shipley said.
</P>
<P>
But she warned that with the opportunities come
responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
"We have been fortunate to inherit a vast ocean region that is
rich in
resources. But we must manage these resources in a prudent and
sustainable manner to preserve our wider ecosystem and the
interests of
future generations," she said.
</P>
<P>
The UNESCO Oceans Charter is aimed at promoting awareness of
the
ocean environment and its importance to society. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
