<DOCNO> XIE19990421.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 06:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon's Budget Deficit Falls in First Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon's budget deficit over
expenditure fell to 36.2 percent in the first quarter this year,
compared with 41.5 percent in the same period in 1998.
</P>
<P>
According to the Ministry of Finance, government expenditure
declined to 1.01 billion U.S. dollars in the first three
months of this year against 1.16 billion dollars in the same
period last year, a drop of 148.6 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Revenues, however, fell to 644 million dollars from 678
million dollars in the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The deficit figure for the first quarter just fell within
the 40 percent target set in the overdue 1999 budget bill
endorsed by the cabinet two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
The bill introduced a hefty tax increase in car gasoline and
customs duties in an effort to raise more government revenues and
bring down huge budget deficit.
</P>
<P>
The budget deficit finished at 43 percent of expenditures in
1998, equal to around 14 percent of gross domestic product(GDP),
from 24 percent of GDP in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said revenues will start improving once
Parliament had approved the budget bill before mid-June. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
