<DOCNO> XIE19990421.0230 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ghana's Power Sector Reform on Course: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Ghanaian Minister of Mines and
Energy Fred Ohene-Kena has reiterated his government's commitment
to the power sector reforms, saying its implementation is on
course.
</P>
<P>
He said Tuesday that in line with this commitment, the
government has come out with a power sector development policy,
which sets out the nature, scope and timing of the reforms, to be
implemented over three years, beginning this year, the Ghana News
Agency (GNA) reported.
</P>
<P>
 At a press briefing in Accra, capital of Ghana, Ohene-Kena
said the main thrust of the reform is to transform Ghana into a
middle-income country within one generation and ensure that
Ghanaians have universal access to electricity.
</P>
<P>
It is also to sustain the transition to an open and liberal
market economy, shifting from the hitherto state administration of
the sector to private investment which will in turn support the
development of human resources and basic infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
Giving an overview of the policy, Ohene-Kena said it covers
policy framework, power sector reform and setting of priorities
over the three-year period.
</P>
<P>
He said the on-going structural and regulatory reforms and the
proposed divestiture of state-owned utilities are part of efforts
to promote private participation in the development of
infrastructure and services.
</P>
<P>
It will ensure that the existing state-owned entities transform
 themselves through public-private partnerships and joint ventures
into commercially viable Ghanaian power utilities and in turn,
assume leadership role in the development of the proposed West
Africa Power Pool.
</P>
<P>
"This is to ensure that electricity supply is made more
reliable, economically efficient and equitable so as to
effectively support the socio- economic development of the
country," he said.
</P>
<P>
Besides, it would enable the sector to attract investment from
Ghanaians and foreign institutional investors, and also from other
private capital sources, including the Ghana Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
However, he said the reform suffered a jolt during the power
crisis that hit the country between December 1997 and the last
quarter of 1998 but an emergency power supply expansion plan had
to be formulated to contain it within a short time frame.
</P>
<P>
As part of the reform, government has since last year created
certain agencies to monitor and advise it on activities of players
in the sector.
</P>
<P>
They include the Public Utilities Regulatory Commission, to
regulate the setting of tariffs for, and enforcement of customer
service obligations of all public utilities, and the Energy
Commission which advises on strategies and policies toward
efficient and safe supply of electricity.
</P>
<P>
Some Independent Power Producers have also been licensed to
build, operate and transmit power.
</P>
<P>
They include Aggreko Plc and Cummins Power Generation Plc of
United Kingdom and KMR Power and Marathon Power, both of United
States.
</P>
<P>
Ohene-Kena said future legislation would have to be passed by
parliament to set up of other relevant agencies that will play a
key role in the reforms.
</P>
<P>
He said the government hopes to create awareness on the reform
policy, details of which would be available in the local media and
on the Internet, to enable the public participate fully in its
progress. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990421.0231 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Foreign Ministry Exhausts Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's Foreign Ministry used
up 391 million Zimbabwean dollars (10.2 million U.S.dollars)
allocated in the 1999 budget, after only three months into the
financial year, but the situation has improved after it got fresh
funds from the Finance Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Although some items on the vote still had funds by the end of
last month, the overall budget had already been exceeded,
prompting the ministry to freeze expenditure while it sought
supplementary funds from Treasury, the daily Herald quoted
ministry officials as saying in a report Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
This poor financial position has caused the ministry to pay its
workers' salaries three days late last month, and the national
airline, Air Zimbabwe, has imposed an embargo on the ministry.
</P>
<P>
Diplomatic bags that the ministry depends on to send documents
to the country's foreign missions and chanceries were not
delivered last month.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Stan Mudenge confirmed the financial
difficulties Tuesday. He blamed the exhaustion of the budget on
budgetary under- provisions, the removal of the equalization fund
from the current budget and the depreciation of the local currency
against major currencies.
</P>
<P>
The minister, who spoke to The Herald in the presence of his
deputy Nicholas Goche, said the situation returned to normal a few
weeks ago when the Ministry of Finance gave his ministry a
supplementary budget. However, he did not disclose how much he
had got from the Finance Ministry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990421.0232 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Gives Kenya 60M Pounds for Malaria Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 21 (Xinhua) -- The British government has
committed 60 million Sterling pounds (about 100 million U.S.
dollars) toward the fight against malaria during the on-going
regional "Roll Back Malaria" meeting in the Kenyan capital.
</P>
<P>
Caroline Sergeant, representative of the UK-based Department
for International Development (DFID), said Tuesday that the Roll
Back Malaria initiative, which is a global project to eradicate
the disease, needed financial support.
</P>
<P>
Sergeant said her organization is enthusiastic about the new
initiative aimed at reducing the occurences of malaria which
claims 2.7 million lives annually, mostly in African countries.
</P>
<P>
During the four-day meeting due to end Thursday, more than 80
governmental officials and medical experts from 14 northern and
eastern African countries and Yemen have been analysing the
situation of the spread of malaria and working out the strategies
to curb the top killer disease in Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
