<DOCNO> XIE19990421.0234 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Electronics Firms Eying Overseas Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, April 21 (Xinhua) -- China's largest machinery and
electronics enterprises are investing overseas to tap into the
international market to increase exports and promote economic
growth, according to Wu Kesong, the vice-chairman of the Haier
Group, China's big electric appliance manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
Haier has investments in Indonesia, the Philippines, Malaysia,
and Yugoslavia and is planning to set up new plants in the Middle
East and America this year, Wu says.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Chunlan Group in Jiangsu Province has signed an
agreement with a large state-owned Russian company to put
technology and equipment in Russia to produce 200,000 air
conditioners a year.
</P>
<P>
Chunlan already has air conditioner and motorcycle factories in
Spain, Russia, Tunisia, Argentina, and the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Many other well-known Chinese companies like the Meiling and
Changhong groups have plans to set up plants in the Middle East
and Africa. Analysts say that the rush to invest abroad represents
the latest official effort to increase exports of high value-added
goods like machinery and electronics.
</P>
<P>
Yang Gengchen, a Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic
Cooperation official, says that the Chinese Government is
encouraging the processing and assembly of products using
materials supplied by overseas companies. He says that the
ministry will select 50 powerful appliance and textile producers
to set up plants in Africa, Central Asia, the Middle East, Eastern
Europe, and South America this year and will give them
preferential treatment in capital allocation, taxes, use of
foreign exchange, and other areas.
</P>
<P>
Official figures show that China exported 66.54 billion US
dollars worth of machinery and electronics goods last year, up 12.
2 percent from 1997, in sharp contrast to the 0.5 percent growth
in total exports.
</P>
<P>
In the first quarter of this year, machinery and electronics
goods exports were worth 16.47 billion US dollars, a jump of 39
percent from the same period of last year. China plans to export
71.5 billion US dollars worth of machinery and electronics goods
this year.
</P>
<P>
Initial figures show machinery and electronics goods accounting
for 35.9 percent of the turnover at the 85th China Export
Commodities Fair in the capital of Guangdong Province that began
on April 15 and will last through the end of the month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
