<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda Needs Foreign Help in Fight Against Drug Smuggling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Uganda needs technical and
logistics help from foreign countries in its fight against drug
abuse and smuggling, a senior police officer told Xinhua Tuesday
evening.
</P>
<P>
Johnson Ayela, Director of Uganda's Anti-Narcotics Unit, said
that his unit is far from enough to completely stop drug abuse and
smuggling in this country because more and more drug traffickers
are using Uganda as a transit.
</P>
<P>
"We already got some help from Britain, Egypt, the United
States, Germany and the United Nations Drug Control Program," the
superintendent said. "But we are still short of hands and
technology to effectively check the drug trafficking activities."
</P>
<P>
The anti-narcotics unit, established in 1986, has only roughly
100 officers deployed at the major airports and border points, he
added.
</P>
<P>
There are many marijuana plantations in the forests in remote
areas in Uganda, he acknowledged. But he said his unit could not
establish the precise location of the plantations because they do
not have helicopters.
</P>
<P>
Poor conditions of infrastructures in these areas also hamper
their efforts against marijuana growing.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan police impounded four kilograms of cocaine in 1996, 1.6
kilograms in 1997 and no cocaine was seized in 1998. A total of
17 kilograms of heroin and 1,000 tons of marijuana have been
seized over the past three years.
</P>
<P>
Ayela said the destinations of the cocaine and heroin are
mostly Europe and South Africa.
</P>
<P>
To better coordinate their efforts in this field,
anti-narcotics police from Uganda, Kenya and Tanzania have met
every six months since 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990421.0238 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Fall Sharply in Tokyo on IMF Outlook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices fell sharply in Tokyo
Wednesday after the International Monetary Fund (IMF) revised
downward its forecast for Japan's economic growth, with the key
Nikkei index closing below 16,500 for the first time in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange declined by 202.09 points, or
1.21 percent, from Tuesday's close to end at 16,495.02.
</P>
<P>
Market players had expected share prices to rise, helped by
Tuesday's upturn on Wall Street, but the IMF's report dampened
market sentiment, stirring stock selling, a dealer said.
</P>
<P>
The IMF said Tuesday it forecasts Japan's economy to shrink by
1.4 percent this year, down from its projection four months
earlier and following the economy's 2.8 percent contraction the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, lost 17.14 points or 1.29 percent to 1,311.
76.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section declined to 492.44 million shares
from Tuesday's 636.53 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Steelmaker NKK was the day's most heavily traded issue.
</P>
<P>
Of the issues listed on the First Section, losers outpaced
gainers 894 to 303, with 126 issues unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990421.0239 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SADC to Monitor Member States' Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 21 (Xinhua) -- The Southern African Development
Community (SADC) is to deploy observer missions to its member
states holding elections this year to assist in the conduct of
free, fair and transparent elections.
</P>
<P>
According to a statement released here Tuesday by the regional
organization, the first two observer missions would go to Malawi
and South Africa this month to monitor elections in the two
countries to be held on May 25 and June 2 respectively.
</P>
<P>
The observer missions selected from representatives of SADC
members and the civil society would be used as a capacity-building
mechanism for electoral commissions in the countries holding
elections, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
It said that other missions would be deployed in Mozambique,
Botswana and Namibia in time for elections this year.
</P>
<P>
Electoral experts from different SADC countries were also
helping the South African independent electoral commission to
prepare for the 1999 elections as part of a program to strengthen
the electoral administration capacity of the electoral commissions
within the SADC. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
