<HEADLINE> Uganda Needs Foreign Help in Fight Against Drug Smuggling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Uganda needs technical and
logistics help from foreign countries in its fight against drug
abuse and smuggling, a senior police officer told Xinhua Tuesday
evening.
</P>
<P>
Johnson Ayela, Director of Uganda's Anti-Narcotics Unit, said
that his unit is far from enough to completely stop drug abuse and
smuggling in this country because more and more drug traffickers
are using Uganda as a transit.
</P>
<P>
"We already got some help from Britain, Egypt, the United
States, Germany and the United Nations Drug Control Program," the
superintendent said. "But we are still short of hands and
technology to effectively check the drug trafficking activities."
</P>
<P>
The anti-narcotics unit, established in 1986, has only roughlysts in remote
areas in Uganda, he acknowledged. But he said his unit could not
establish the precise location of the plantations because they do
not have helicopters.
</P>
<P>
Poor conditions of infrastructures in these areas also hamper
their efforts against marijuana growing.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan police impounded four kilograms of cocaine in 1996, 1.6
kilograms nce 1996. 
</P>
