<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shaanxi Builds Environmental Protects with Foreign Loans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Northwest China's Shaanxi Province
has used 170 million U.S. dollars in loans and donations from
abroad to create seven key environmental protection projects over
the past few years.
</P>
<P>
The largest of these is a comprehensive pollution control
project in Xi'an, the provincial capital, and the cities of
Xianyang and Tongchuan. The Asian Development Bank offered 156
million U.S. dollars to build a steam power-generating system in
these three cities, replacing coal with natural gas as the fuel in
urban districts, and to treat dust generated by a cement plant,
said Yang Jianjun, an official with the Shaanxi Provincial
Environmental Protection Bureau.
</P>
<P>
Other projects include the establishment of an automatic air-
monitoring system in Xi'an and Weinan, a Sino-Japanese venture to
control air pollution in developing countries, a program for
protecting natural resources in the Qinling Mountain range, and a
training course for environmental planning, management, and
monitoring.
</P>
<P>
Shaanxi is one of the most heavily polluted areas in China as
coal serves as 75 percent of the fuel in the province, and the
provincial capital of Xi'an is listed as one of the 10 most
polluted cities in the world. Tongchuan, a coal and building
material production center, is enveloped in smog all year round
and cannot be identified easily from satellite. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
