<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SADC to Monitor Member States' Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 21 (Xinhua) -- The Southern African Development
Community (SADC) is to deploy observer missions to its member
states holding elections this year to assist in the conduct of
free, fair and transparent elections.
</P>
<P>
According to a statement released here Tuesday by the regional
organization, the first two observer missions would go to Malawi
and South Africa this month to monitor elections in the two
countries to be held on May 25 and June 2 respectively.
</P>
<P>
The observer missions selected from representatives of SADC
members and the civil society would be used as a capacity-building
mechanism for electoral commissions in the countries holding
elections, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
It said that other missions would be deployed in Mozambique,
Botswana and Namibia in time for elections this year.
</P>
<P>
Electoral experts from different SADC countries were also
helping the South African independent electoral commission to
prepare for the 1999 elections as part of a program to strengthen
the electoral administration capacity of the electoral commissions
within the SADC. 
</P>
</TEXT>
