<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stock Exchange Records 32 Percent First Quarter Drop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Turnover on the Shanghai Stock
Exchange dropped 32 percent on an annual basis to 156.4 billion
yuan during the first quarter of the year in spite of active
trading in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
Analysts attributed the plunge in total volume to low-level
investor interest in the days leading up to this year's
traditional Spring Festival on February 16 and the extended
trading break during the holiday season.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark Composite Stock Index (CSI) ended March at 1,158.
05 points, up 14 points on the start of the year. The SSE-30 Index,
based on 30 blue chip shares, finished the first quarter at 2,747
points, down 16 points.
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai bourse raised funds totaling 3.1 billion yuan from
eight new stocks listed during the first three months. The 486
companies listed on the Shanghai exchange by the end of March
involved share issues valued at 132.38 billion yuan and market
capitalization of well over 1.1 trillion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The quarterly trading volume declined on an annual basis, with
market development trends since the Spring Festival indicating
that strong investor confidence, according to analysts.
</P>
<P>
Economists noted that a strong economy during 1999 will provide
the fundamental basis for stable development of the stock market.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese economy grew 8.3 percent during the first quarter,
with the economic growth rate for 1998 ending at 7.8 percent and
this year's rate expected to hit seven percent.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the volume of fund transactions and state
treasury bonds hit 18.84 billion yuan and 387.78 billion yuan
respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
