<DOCNO> XIE19990421.0269 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Merrill Lynch Examines Changes Brought by E-Commerce </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Electronic commerce has
altered and is continuing to significantly change traditional
business philosophies across a broad spectrum of industries,
commerce and finance, according to a Merrill Lynch research report
released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
E-commerce is a far-reaching business concept, not just a
unique technology, said analysts at Merrill Lynch, one of the
world's leading financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
They examined how the e-commerce is altering the ways of doing
business in different industries from advertising to
telecommunication services. They also discussed e-commerce's
implications for accounting practices as well as government
regulation worldwide.
</P>
<P>
The report said the revolutionary changes prompted by e-
commerce could also increase outsourcing and motivate companies in
non-Internet industries to re-engineer themselves in order to take
advantage of the new technology.
</P>
<P>
Information technology which includes e-commerce, the report
said, has shown exponential growth and already contributes
meaningfully to the macroeconomic performance of the United States.
This includes decline of inflation, strong productivity gains and
continued growth in employment.
</P>
<P>
Companies in information-oriented industries such as banking,
brokerage and publishing, already have been profoundly affected by
e-commerce, the study found.
</P>
<P>
Other industries, such as freight forwarding and insurance, are
now re-defining themselves. Still others, such as real estate,
should expect to feel e-commerce's influence as the Internet tends
to "cannibalize" retail sales away from store-based retailers,
reducing in some cases the underlying value of retail real estate,
the study suggested. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
