<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka Gets Aid Commitments of US$2.04 Billion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh has got fresh aid
commitments of 2.04 billion U.S. dollars for the 1999-2000 fiscal
year in the Bangladesh Development Forum Meeting that concluded
Tuesday in Paris, press reports here said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
This year's commitment is 104 million dollars more than last
year's 1.9 billion dollars. But, the commitment for last year rose
to 2.22 billion dollars when the donors extended their financial
cooperation in flood rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
The Bangladeshi government sought 2.04 billion dollars from the
donors, who were committed to providing the same amount,
Bangladesh's Finance Minister S.A.M.S. Kabria was quoted as saying
in Paris right after the two-day meeting which was earlier known
as the Aid Consortium Meeting.
</P>
<P>
There was no scope of confusion about the commitment of aid,
Kabria said, adding that the donors found the required amount
"reasonable" and "realistic" and subsequently they agreed to
provide it.
</P>
<P>
This year's meeting further strengthened the relations between
the donors and the Bangladeshi government, he stated.
</P>
<P>
Kabria pointed out that like previous years, donors also
underscored the need for accelerating the reform process in
different sectors, including finance and banking, administration,
legal system, education, health and power.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh has made significant progress in implementing
reforms but many more challenges are still to be met, Kabria
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
