<DOCNO> XIE19990421.0275 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Leading Romanian Opposition Against Opening Sky to NATO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Romania's largest opposition
party, the Social Democratic Party (SDP), said Tuesday it opposes
giving NATO "unlimited" access to Romania's sky, noting NATO's
military action on Yugoslavia has worsened the tragic situation
there.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued after a meeting between SDP Chairman Ion
Iliescu, also former Romanian president, and President Emil
Constantinescu, the party said the Romanian parliament had already
clarified Romania's principled stand on the Kosovo crisis in a
resolution on March 30, in which Romania recognizes Yugoslavia's
territorial integrity and sovereignty and appeals for respect for
the legitimate rights of the ethnic Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
It noted that under an agreement reached last October, Romania
permits NATO airplanes to enter its sky only under "urgent and
unexpected circumstances." The agreement is still effective and
any new decision on this matter by the authority should not go
beyond it, it added.
</P>
<P>
It said if NATO's request for "unlimited" access to Romania's
sky is to facilitate its military attacks on Yugoslavia, Romania's
meeting the request would mean unilaterally violating its
friendship, good-neighborliness and cooperation treaty with
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The treaty stipulates that either side must not provide any
support for a third party attacking the other, still less open its
territory and sky to the third party.
</P>
<P>
The SDP appealed to the parliament and government to work
actively for a political solution to the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, the Supreme Council of Romanian Defense decided to
meet NATO's request for "unlimited" access to Romania's sky.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that President Constantinescu consulted with
leaders of the ruling coalition and opposition before the decision.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
