<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka's Star Sprinter Will be Cleared: Lawyer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's top woman sprinter
Susanthika Jayasinghe has very good reasons to be acquitted of all
doping charges by the International Amateur Athletic Federation (
IAAF) at the hearing in Monaco this week, said her lawyer Daya
Perera.
</P>
<P>
"We are all confident that justice will be done to Susanthika
at this hearing," Perera told The Island newspaper published on
Wednesday, adding that if by chance the IAAF penalizes her they
are ready to appeal to even a higher body.
</P>
<P>
Susanthika's lawyer said the main point at the inquiry will be
the questionable and the highly irregular manner in which her off
season drug test was conducted last March.
</P>
<P>
"There are certain rules and all those had been simply violated
by the Sri Lankan authorities who conducted the test," he said.
</P>
<P>
Susanthika, a 200 meters silver medallist at the World Athletic
Championships in Athens, is Sri Lanka's only athlete ever to win a
medal at the world class events.
</P>
<P>
She was suspended in April after testing positive for the
steroid nandrolone but had her ban lifted by the Sri Lankan
athletics authorities.
</P>
<P>
The IAAF Doping Commission has recommended a two-year ban but a
final decision on whether to implement it, reduce it or exonerate
the athlete depends on the arbitration panel's decision, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
Jayasinghe left Sri Lanka in January to train in the United
States to prepare for the World Athletic Championships to be held
in Spain in July. 
</P>
</TEXT>
