<HEADLINE> 1 Killed, Thousands Displaced in Rains in Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, April 21 (Xinhua) -- One person was reported killed in
a landslide and thousands were rendered homeless Sri Lanka as
heavy rains accompanied by gale force winds lashed many parts of
the country in the last two days.
</P>
<P>
Torrential rains poured on the capital, Colombo, since Tuesday
night, and a number of roads were flooded.
</P>
<P>
Subscribers complained of newspaper delivery delay as workers
on the early shift were postponed by heavy rains.
</P>
<P>
The Meteorology Department said that persisting low-level
disturbances in the atmosphere in the southwest of the Bay of
Bengal was the cause of the sudden storm which hit the island
nation on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
A landslide and flood caused by heavy rain in Ratnapura
District in Sabaragamuwa Province on Monday night left one dead
and 5,000 homeless, said N.D. Hettiarachchi, deputy director of
Relief and Rehabilitation of the Social Services Department.
</P>
<P>
A sum of 500,000 rupees (7,300 U.S. dollars) has been released
to the Ratnapura District secretary to provide food for flood
victims.
</P>
<P>
The Meteorology Department has sent out a bad weather warning
to fishermen in the country's coasts as occasional showers with
thunder and gusty winds can be expected.
</P>
<P>
"Skies will be cloudy and intermittent showers accompanied by
thunder and fairly strong winds will be experienced in Western,
Southern, Sabaragamuwa and Central Province," said Deputy Director
of the Meteorology Department Jayatilaka Banda. 
</P>
</TEXT>
