<DOCNO> XIE19990421.0286 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WHO Health Research Meeting Held in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, April 21 (Xinhua) -- The World Health Organization
(WHO) Southeast Asia Advisory Committee on health research is
meeting here to monitor and evaluate the implementation of
national, regional and global strategies adopted by the countries
in the region.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time for Myanmar to host such a meeting.
</P>
<P>
The four-day 24th session of the committee, which began
Tuesday, is attended by officials of the Myanmar Health Ministry,
WHO representatives from its head office in Geneva and the
Southeast Asia office.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar Minister of Health Major-General Ket Sein said at the
opening session that the world is encountering challenges as it
enters the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
A demographic transition, due to a high rate of increase in the
number of people older than 65 years, is posing significant
pressure on social support systems, he said.
</P>
<P>
He warned that global health will remain threatened by new and
old infectious diseases such as malaria, tuberculosis and AIDS.
</P>
<P>
He said Myanmar has made achievements in expanding the coverage
of immunization against six children's diseases, particularly in
efforts to eliminate polio by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The country has also made progress in improving access to safe
water supply and sanitary excreta disposal, in preventing iodine
deficiency disorders and in eliminating leprosy by the year 2000,
he said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Myanmar is one of the leading centers for the WHO
in leprosy drug trial.
</P>
<P>
He said Myanmar has been collaborating with Japan National
Institute of Health since 1995 in research on molecular
epidemiology of HIV transmission in Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
He added that researchers of Myanmar and countries of the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations have also been cooperating
in solving health problems of the region.
</P>
<P>
Along with other countries in the region, Myanmar has adopted
primary health care as a key approach to achieving the goal of
"Health for All By 2000." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
