<DOCNO> XIE19990421.0287 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Calls For Actions to Prevent Financial Crises in Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 20 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton on
Tuesday urged the international community to take steps to
strengthen the global financial system in a bid to prevent
financial crises from reaching catastrophic stages in the future.
</P>
<P>
After meeting with his top economic advisers, Clinton said the
United States would work with finance ministers from the world's
major economies, meeting in Washington this weekend, to build
support for his financial proposals before a June summit in
Germany of leaders of the major industrial economies.
</P>
<P>
"Some economies once in crisis are beginning to turn the corner,
but substantial risks and challenges remain," Clinton said. "This
is not a moment for complacency. It's a moment to act to prevent
financial crises from reaching catastrophic stages in the future."
</P>
<P>
Urging people to think about what the world has been through in
the last two years because of the problems in the global financial
system, Clinton stressed that "there are few more important things
for leaders to be doing than working on building a stable
financial architecture for the new century."
</P>
<P>
Outlining his agenda of financial reforms, the president said "
we industrial countries should take steps to reduce the entire
financial system's vulnerability to rapid capital flows and excess
leverage."
</P>
<P>
He said that the private sector should assume an appropriate
share of responsibility for responding to the financial crises.
</P>
<P>
"Developing countries should take more responsibility as well
by strengthening financial regulation and bank supervision and
developing sustainable debt management policies, thus avoiding
excessive reliance on short-term debt," he said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton also urged the international financial institutions to
focus their efforts on encouraging developing countries to adopt
sustainable exchange rate regimes and the macroeconomic policies
necessary to support them.
</P>
<P>
To ensure that the most vulnerable citizens do not bear the
brunt of the financial crises, the president said the
International Monetary Fund and the World Bank must "pay more
attention to social safety nets, working with countries to lay
strong foundations during good times and to maintain adequate
protections during bad times."
</P>
<P>
Clinton also called on rich creditors to provide assistance to
the poorest countries because these nations are burdened with
unsustainable levels of debt.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said that Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin is to give
more details on the proposals on Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
