<HEADLINE> Twenty-five Killed in Colorado School Shooting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 20 (Xinhua) -- As many as 25 people were
killed Tuesday as two heavily armed young men opened fire at a
high school southwest of Denver, capital of the Colorado State of
the United States.
</P>
<P>
The gunmen, believed to be former students at Columbine High
School, were found dead at the library after the shooting.
</P>
<P>
They, wearing black trench coats and masks, moved calmly
through the school library and giggled as they shot at students at
lunch time.
</P>
<P>
"They were just shooting. They don't care who they shot at,"
one witness said.
</P>
<P>
However, some witnesses said the gunmen, armed with automatic
weapons and explosives, appeared to have two particular targets --
minority students and popular athletes, apparently taking revenge
at the school with 1,800 students.
</P>
<P>
Some students said the killers might have been members of a
group of eight to ten students who wear black trench coats every
day and are known as the "Trench Coat Mafia".
</P>
<P>
The social tensions between the school athletes and the "Trench
Coat Mafia" may have been one factor in the attack, which was
considered the worst mass shooting in the U.S. history.
</P>
<P>
A total of 18 others were hospitalized, some in critical
condition.
</P>
<P>
Deploring the mass slaying of students, President Bill Clinton
said the federal government will provide any assistance needed to
deal with the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
"We don't know yet all the how's and why's of this tragedy," he
told reporters in the briefing room of the White House.
</P>
<P>
"The prayers of the American people are with you," the
president told the victims and survivors.
</P>
<P>
A series of school shootings since 1997 shocked the nation and
led to calls for tighter security and closer monitoring of
troubled students.
</P>
<P>
Two were killed at a school in Pearl, Mississippi, three at
West Paducah, Kansas, five at Jonesboro, Arkansas, and two at a
school in Springfield, Oregon.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics released by U.S. Department of
Education last year, attacks with weapons accounted for almost 11,
000 incidents in public schools during the 1996-97 school year.
</P>
</TEXT>
