<HEADLINE> Japan's Trade Surplus Up 23 Percent in 1998 from 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Japan's merchandise trade surplus
increased to 14,096.9 billion yen (about 118.8 billion dollars) in
the fiscal year of 1998, up 23.1 percent from the previous year,
the Finance Ministry said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The ministry attributed the rise, which has gained for two
fiscal years in a row, to a plunge in imports.
</P>
<P>
Japan's exports dropped 3.8 percent to 49,450.7 billion yen (
about 416.6 billion dollars) in the fiscal of 1998, while imports
totaled 35,353.8 billion yen (about 297.8 billion dollars), both
marking the first decline in five fiscal years, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
Japan's politically sensitive trade surplus with the United
States stood at 6,687.2 billion yen (56.3 billion dollars), up 23.
5 percent for the second straight year-on-year rise, the ministry
said.
</P>
<P>
Trade surplus with Asian neighbors plunged 36.3 percent to 3,
803.8 billion yen (about 32.1 billion dollars), with Japan's
exports dropping 18.0 percent and imports dipping 10.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
With the 15-member European Union (EU), Japan's trade surplus
soared 42.5 percent to a record high of 4,265.4 billion yen (about
35.9 billion dollars), the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
Japan's merchandise trade balance is measured on the basis of
goods clearing customs and is reported before adjustment for
seasonal factors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
