<HEADLINE> 150,000 Die of Cancer Per Year in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 21 (Xinhua) -- About 200,000 people in Bangladesh
become victims of cancer every year and at least 150,000 of them
die of the disease, The Independent English daily reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The figures were revealed at a meeting of the National Council
for Cancer Control (NCCC) held here Tuesday, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Reviewing the medical efforts for treatment and prevention of
the disease, the NCCC stressed the need for raising public
awareness of the causes that may lead to the development of
cancer.
</P>
<P>
The meeting also emphasized the need for launching a campaign
against smoking as nearly 50 percent of all cancer cases are
believed to be caused by tobacco.
</P>
<P>
A new 36-member NCCC was formed at the meeting, which was
presided over by Health and Family Welfare Minister Salahuddin
Yusuf. 
</P>
