<HEADLINE> Premier Zhu Winds up Successful Visit to Canada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VANCOUVER, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji left
Vancouver, British Columbia, Tuesday afternoon for Beijing,
winding up his successful visit to Canada.
</P>
<P>
Before his departure, overseas Chinese in Vancouver held a
grand farewell banquet in his honor with an attendance of more
than 1,000 guests.
</P>
<P>
During his seven-day stay in Canada, Zhu held talks with
Canadian Prime Minister Jean Chretien on bilateral relations and
international and regional issues.
</P>
<P>
The talks produced a number of agreements for cooperation in
various fields between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also made significant progress on China's entry
into the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the banquet, hosted by Vancouver's Overseas Chinese
Welcoming Committee, Zhu said his visit to Canada has achieved
great success, not only in having reached the business and trade
agreements, but also in promoting contacts, expanding consensus
and strengthening friendship between the two peoples.
</P>
<P>
During his stay, Zhu visited six cities from the Atlantic coast
to the Pacific, including St. John's, Ottawa, Toronto, Calgary,
Victoria and Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
Zhu stressed that every success he made during his stay in
Canada was the logical result of following the guideline of
nurturing the Sino-Canadian comprehensive and cooperative
partnership and bringing it into the next century, set in 1997 by
Chinese President Jiang Zemin and Chretien.
</P>
<P>
Credit for the success should also be given to Canadian friends
and overseas Chinese, Zhu said. Their persistent efforts for the
exchanges and cooperation between the two countries deserved the
Chinese government and Chinese people's respect and gratitude, he
added.
</P>
<P>
China is becoming increasingly stronger thanks to the 20 years
of reforms now still under way, which have helped it tide over
financial crisis in Asia and the unprecedented wild flooding
across the country, Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
China has now a very healthy economy, which is opening up an
even wider market and more opportunities for foreign investors in
various fields, he added.
</P>
<P>
That also was an ingredient for the success of the visit, he
said, calling on overseas Chinese and Canadian entrepreneurs to
explore more opportunities in China.
</P>
<P>
Zhu also took the occasion to refute the cliche of so-call "
independent Taiwan," reaffirming the Chinese government's
determination to reunify Taiwan with the motherland.
</P>
<P>
He said Taiwan has always been an inalienable part of China in
history and that those advocate "independence of Taiwan" have
deliberately ignored the fact and betrayed their ancestors.
</P>
<P>
China seeks peaceful settlement for the reunification of Taiwan
with the motherland, but would not renounce the use of force when
necessary, Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
He said he was sure that those advocating "independence of
Taiwan" will be doomed to failure.
</P>
<P>
Canadian Minister of Fisheries and Oceans David Anderson and
Premier of British Columbia Glen Clark were invited to the banquet.
In their enthusiastic remarks, they expressed their
congratulations to Zhu's successful visit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
