<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: ABCs of Macao SAR Basic Law (44) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Following is part 44 of a
question and answer series on the Basic Law of the Macao Special
Administrative Region (MSAR).
</P>
<P>
Will the financial institutions in the MSAR be able to conduct
financial businesses freely? Will Renminbi become a legal tender
in the MSAR?
</P>
<P>
Owing to the small size of Macao's economy and some other
factors, the financial sector in Macao was not developed until a
banking act was promulgated in 1970.
</P>
<P>
Many private banks or money-lockers registered as banks one
after another and banks in Hong Kong and other overseas banks
started to set up branches in Macao.
</P>
<P>
The banking industry has entered a new stage of development
since 1982 when Macao promulgated a new banking act. A number of
influential overseas banks such as the Banque National de Paris of
France, the Citibank and Standard Chartered Bank were permitted to
set up branches in Macao.
</P>
<P>
Financial companies and investment centers have also been set
up and the deposit and loan business has expanded rapidly.
</P>
<P>
At present, the financial sector in Macao is controlled by
banks, which are the main channels of financing for companies,
enterprises and residents.
</P>
<P>
So far, Macao has no stock exchange of its own, no standard
securities companies nor listed companies. The amount of gold and
stocks traded on behalf of clients by financial institutions that
are also engaged in securities business is limited.
</P>
<P>
In Macao, foreign exchange is freely convertible, the
Government does not exercise any control on foreign exchange, and
there is no developed foreign exchange market. In short, the
financial industry in Macao is still in its infant stage and has
great potential for growth.
</P>
<P>
To protect the financial industry in Macao and facilitate its
steady growth, the Basic Law stipulates that the monetary and
financial systems of the MSAR shall be prescribed by law, that the
Government of the MSAR shall, on its own, formulate monetary and
financial policies, safeguard the free operation of
financial markets and all kinds of financial institutions, and
regulate and supervise them in accordance with law, after the
return of Macao.
</P>
<P>
The residents of Macao, including those residing overseas, may
continue to be freely engaged in financial activities such as
obtaining bank loans, insurance, foreign exchange transactions,
property mortgage, investment in gold and securities, etc.
</P>
<P>
A legal tender is a currency whose circulation in a country or
region is made compulsory by the country or region through
enacting a law.
</P>
<P>
The currencies that are in circulation in Macao are the Macao
Pataca and Hong Kong dollars, but the Macao Pataca is the only
currency that has the status of a legal tender.
</P>
<P>
The National Bank of Ultramarine, a Portuguese-funded bank in
Macao, had since 1905 been authorized by the Portuguese Macao
Government to issue the Macao Pataca.
</P>
<P>
On October 16, 1995, the Chinese and Portuguese sides agreed
through consultation that the Bank of China in Macao may also
issue the Macao Pataca.
</P>
<P>
To ensure that the MSAR enjoy a high degree of autonomy in the
financial field, Article 108 of the Basic Law makes the following
provisions:
</P>
<P>
The Macao Pataca, as the legal tender in the MSAR, shall
continue to circulate.
</P>
<P>
The authority to issue the Macao Pataca shall be vested in the
Government of the MSAR which may authorize designated banks to
perform or continue to perform the function of its agents in the
issuance of Macao Pataca.
</P>
<P>
The Macao Pataca shall be freely convertible.
</P>
<P>
It is clear from these provisions that Renminbi will not be the
legal tender in the MSAR. The banks that are previously
authorized to issue the Macao Pataca shall continue to do so,
provided that they are authorized by the Government of the MSAR.
</P>
<P>
The Macao Pataca that the Macao residents have can be converted
into various foreign currencies.
</P>
<P>
The issuance of the Macao Pataca has been backed by a 100
percent reserve fund. Large business transactions in Macao are
usually settled in Hong Kong dollars.
</P>
<P>
As Macao is small in area and the circulation and issue of
Macao Pataca is not on a large scale, it is further provided in
Article 108 of the Basic Law that the issue of the Macao Pataca
must be backed by a 100 percent reserve fund.
</P>
<P>
This is what the government finance can afford and is conducive
to the stability of the Macao Pataca and to its role of leverage
in the economy of the Region.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990421.0293 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
