<HEADLINE> Banana Exporting Countries Look for New Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, April 20 (Xinhua) -- The Banana Exporting
Countries Union (BECU) is looking for new markets in China and the
Middle East, a high official of the organization said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Tax restrictions imposed by the European Union on the Central
American countries forced BECU members to turn to the gigantic
Asian market, Beatriz Garcia, coordinator of the Inter American
Agriculture Institute with the Banana Union, said.
</P>
<P>
Describing China as a very successful market, he added, "If
each of the 1.2 billion Chinese citizens ate just one banana
produced by the BECU countries, the problem of the search for new
markets would be resolved."
</P>
<P>
With respect to the Middle East markets, she said although they
are unstable, the banana producers are seeking an opening.
</P>
<P>
The banana producing countries are awaiting the implementation
of the tariff resolution by the World Trade Organization (WTO)
against the European Union countries for their restrictions placed
in 1989 on banana importation from Latin America.
</P>
<P>
By the end of March, the WTO ruled in favor of the U.S.
companies which operated in the region and had requested the
opening of the markets.
</P>
<P>
A panel of WTO arbitrators earlier this month gave the United
States the go-ahead in principle for 191.4 million dollars per
year of trade sanctions against the EU, while ruling in a separate
report that the EU's import policy for bananas was not in
compliance with WTO rules.
</P>
<P>
But the ruling is still not being carried out due to EU's red
tape and it will be a long trial process before it takes proper
effect, Garcia noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
