<HEADLINE> Colombian President Confident of Formal Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTA FE DE BOGOTA, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Colombian President
Andres Pastrana expressed confidence that the peace talks resumed
on Tuesday will lead to formal negotiations between the government
and guerrillas before May 7.
</P>
<P>
Pastrana said he was sure that the meeting would get the two
sides back to the negotiation table before May 7, the date on
which the demilitarized zone agreement runs out.
</P>
<P>
The Colombian government resumed peace negotiations Tuesday in
a southern territory that was demilitarized last year with the
largest guerrilla group of the country, the Revolutionary Armed
Forces of Colombia (FARC).
</P>
<P>
The demilitarized zone was part of FARC's precondition for the
talks last year. When it unilaterally suspended the talks in
January for the alleged government slackness in fighting rightist
paramilitary forces, Pastrana extended the deadline for bringing
the demilitarized zone under government control from January 7 to
May 7 to save the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Pastrana said that the most important thing for the time being
was to look for mechanisms to reach an agenda on the start of
formal negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The list of topics proposed by both parties include fighting
against the paramilitary troops and elimination of illegal crops
in the zones controlled by the FARC.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Pastrana requested the second largest
guerrilla group of the country, the National Liberation Army (ELN),
to unconditionally release the 32 passengers of a commercial
airline they hijacked last week before the talks were opened.
</P>
<P>
Pastrana reportedly said Tuesday he might agree to the ELN's
demand for its own demilitarized zone in the north in order to
further peace talks with the guerrilla group, but stressed that
the move depended on the release of the hostages.
</P>
<P>
The armed conflicts in Colombia, which have lasted for nearly
five decades, are the most protracted in Latin America, claiming
more than 35,000 lives in the last ten years alone. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
