<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Elderly Encouraged to Get Higher Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 21 (Xinhua) -- More preferential policies and
better management are needed to develop "senior citizens'
universities, today's China Daily quotes an expert as saying.
</P>
<P>
Yu Guohou, vice-president of the China National Committee on
Aging said that China intends to offer its constantly expanding
aged population more opportunities for higher education.
</P>
<P>
The country is encouraging the development of education for
senior citizens, according to a law on the protection of the
rights and interests of the elderly, which took effect in 1996.
</P>
<P>
"Such encouragement should be reflected in concrete policies,"
Yu said.
</P>
<P>
Sponsors should be found to support these universities, he said.
These could include individually and collectively owned
enterprises, privately firms and joint ventures.
</P>
<P>
Most senior citizens' universities in China are now run by
administrative departments such as local committees for elderly
people.
</P>
<P>
Yu called on all sectors of society to contribute more funding
for such universities.
</P>
<P>
"Education for the elderly should be listed in the national
education development program and receive State funding," Yu said.
</P>
<P>
The improvement of senior citizens universities depends largely
on how such a program is managed, he said.
</P>
<P>
The teaching staff in these universities consists predominately
of retired teachers.
</P>
<P>
Since the first of these universities was set up in Shandong
Province in 1983, China has witnessed a boom in the sector. There
are now more than 13,000 senior citizens' universities with 1.01
million students, according to association statistics.
</P>
<P>
However, people attending these universities account for less
than one percent of the country's elderly population.
</P>
<P>
Yu estimated that this figure would climb to two to three
percent in the first decade or two of the next century, the paper
says. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990421.0302 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study: El Nino May Help Slow Global Warming </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 20 (Xinhua) -- New study suggests that El
Nino may help slow the global warming, though it has been blamed
for many climate disorders such as floods and droughts, according
to a report published in the Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
The report said Richard A. Feely and his colleagues at the U.S.
National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration have found that
from 1991 to 1994, when El Nino was said to contribute to the
warming of the Pacific, the carbon dioxide the ocean released was
in fact 30 percent to 80 percent less than usual.
</P>
<P>
The study believed that because carbon dioxide is one of the
primary greenhouse gases contributing to the warming of the planet,
the decrease of this greenhouse gas may therefore help slow the
global warming. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990421.0303 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Should Step up Fiscal System Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 21 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government should
enhance its financial strength and change its means of economic
management in developing a market economy.
</P>
<P>
The government has played a vital role in promoting China's
economic reform in the past two decades. However, it has also
failed to fulfill its duty in some aspects of economic management
and has led with an unduly heavy hand in other areas.
</P>
<P>
To propel an overall market-oriented development of the
national economy, the State should reform its investment and
financial systems, according to an article by Guo Shuqing, vice-
governor of southwestern Guizhou Province, published in today's
China Daily.
</P>
<P>
Under a new investment system, industries should be opened to
various investors and competition introduced to monopoly
industries through reorganization, stock listings and public bids.
</P>
<P>
Financial methods should be diversified, in particular, direct
financing such as the issuance of stocks and bonds should be
emphasized. The government should control investment activities
indirectly through adjusting fiscal, monetary and tax policies.
</P>
<P>
The State should also further commercialize State-owned banks
while encouraging the development of local or regional commercial
banks to facilitate competition between banks.
</P>
<P>
The central bank should apply asset-liability ratio criteria in
their management of commercial banks. And the State should also
make great efforts to develop capital markets.
</P>
<P>
Other tasks the government needs to complete include monetizing
income distribution, stepping up urbanization and opening wider to
the outside world.
</P>
<P>
However, currently, reforms of the State-owned enterprises,
State-owned banks, the social security system and government
institutions are all impeded by unfinished fiscal reform.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, a more imperative task China faces in the coming
years is establishing a stronger and standardized fiscal system,
which is crucial for the realization of the government's role in
developing a market economy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
