<HEADLINE> Thai Economic Growth Projected at 4 Percent for 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 21 (Xinhua) -- The Bangkok Bank's research
department has projected that Thailand's economic growth could
reach 4 to 5 percent next year, higher than the government's
projection of 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
Nimit Nontapunthawat, the bank's executive vice president who
oversees the research department was quoted Wednesday by The
Nation as saying the economy could grow beyond 3 percent on the
back of the 110-billion-baht (2.97 billion U.S. dollars) budget
deficit in next fiscal year, or 2 percent of the gross domestic
product (GDP).
</P>
<P>
However, the achievement of the growth target will depend on
how efficiently the government distributes the budget to related
units, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the research department has also revised its economic
forecast for this year from a contraction of 0.4 percent to a
growth of 1 percent. The revision was due to the changing economic
environment.
</P>
<P>
he said the economic stimulus package announced by the Thai
government on March 30 will help boost the country's economy this
year. Moreover, commercial banks are showing some progress in
their recaptalization and the trend of non-performing loans is
also showing a downward drift.
</P>
<P>
According to Nimit, there should be an improvement in the
economic conditions of Asian countries in the year 2000 after
their economies bottom out this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
