<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan-made Bio-chemical Weapons Found in Northeast China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Many weapons left by the Japanese
army during its invasion of China more than six decades ago were
discovered recently at one old garrison in Dongning County in
northeast China's Heilongjiang Province.
</P>
<P>
The weapons include over 800 shells, landmines, anti-tank
grenades, revolvers, guns, swords, and more than 20 bombs, one
weighing more than 100 kilograms.
</P>
<P>
Military expert Tian Penghan confirmed after an investigation
that one of the bombs contained bacteriological material, and five
of the shells were filled with toxic gas. Experts said this was
the first time bio-chemical weapons have ever been found at the
Dongning garrisons.
</P>
<P>
The old Dongning garrisons are located along the Sino-Russian
border, and extend for 20 kilometers. They served as a rear
supply base for the Japanese army during its aggression in China,
and six of these former underground garrisons have been discovered,
each covering an area of about 10,000 square meters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
