<HEADLINE> Yugoslav Envoy: Halt to NATO Strikes "Precondition" for Political </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NATO "should stop its aggression (of Yugoslavia), (and) this is
the pre-condition for everything", Jovanoic said in an exclusive
interview with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
"We are not a country opposing a political settlement. Just
opposite, we are a country endorsing the political settlement," he
said. "We are open to the political settlement."
</P>
<P>
In response to peace initiatives recently proposed by Germany,
Italy and U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan, Jovanovic, former
foreign minister of Yugoslavia, said that the political solution "
should be based on the full respect of the sovereignty and
territorial integrity of the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia, and
the guarantee of equal rights for all citizens and all national
communities living in the province."
</P>
<P>
Last Friday, Yugoslavia rejected the key elements of Annan's
Kosovo initiative, saying an international military force in
Yugoslavia is unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
A political solution can only be achieved "in direct talks
between our government and ethnic Albanians" in Kosovo, where
ethnic Albanians make up some 90 percent of the province's
population of 2 million.
</P>
<P>
"The international representatives will be invited (to the
talks) only as witnesses, not as mediators," he said, "because our
bad experience told us that these international mediators will
impose solutions on us."
</P>
<P>
In the fruitless peace talks in France, Western powers have
insisted Belgrade accept the military presence in Kosovo. NATO is
bombing Yugoslavia in intention to force the Yugoslav Government
to admit foreign troops into the Serbian province.
</P>
<P>
"What NATO is doing is to put the only remaining part of the
Balkan under its direct military control, that's the real policy
of NATO," said Jovanovic, who earlier slammed the ongoing NATO
bombardment as a move to pave the way for NATO's eastward
expansion and its new strategy in the coming new century.
</P>
<P>
"NATO has set a very bad and dangerous precedent in the world,
and that is the omen for the future development" at the turn of
century, he said.
</P>
<P>
NATO, without the authorization of the U.N. Security Council,
began its military attacks against Yugoslavia on March 24, a
sovereign and independent member of the UN, thus violating the UN
Charter and international law.
</P>
<P>
So far, 600 civilians have been killed and 5,000 wounded, some
of them in critical conditions, Jovanovic said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, NATO's strikes have also created a large exodus of
refugees and serious humanitarian crisis in Yugoslavia.  
</P>
</TEXT>
