<HEADLINE> Thailand to Delay Communications Liberalization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Thailand will delay the
liberalization of its telecommunications industry by a year,
Wednesday's Bangkok Post reported.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted the Telephone Organization of Thailand (TOT)
as saying the legal framework allowing a free telecommunications
market is unlikely to be in place before October next year, 12
months behind schedule.
</P>
<P>
The industry could not be fully liberalized this year, but
would be so by the end of next year, said Withu Rukswanichpongs,
the TOT's senior executive vice-president.
</P>
<P>
He said legislation had made much slower progress than
expected.
</P>
<P>
Responsible for domestic services, the TOT owns 41 percent of
the installed telephone lines nationwide and 51 percent of those
that have been connected.
</P>
<P>
It also grants concessions to two fixed-line operators,
TelecomAsia (TA) and Thai Telephone &AMP; Telecommunications (TT&AMP;T).
</P>
<P>
The TOT and the Communications Authority of Thailand (CAT),
which runs international networks, are due to be privatized soon
as part of a liberalization move of the Thai telecommunications
market.
</P>
<P>
Under this process, originally slated for the third quarter of
this year, the concession system agreed with TA, TT&AMP;T and other
license holders will be scrapped.
</P>
<P>
Withu said it was still unclear how the concession system would
be converted, but added that it would either be transformed into
shares or markets could be split up on a geographical basis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
