<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia Calls for Help to End NATO Strikes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 20 (Xinhua) -- A senior Yugoslav diplomat
Tuesday called on the international community to help bring an end
to the ongoing NATO bombing in order to restore peace and security
in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview with Xinhua, Vladislav Jovanovic,
charge d'affaires of the Yugoslav Mission to the United Nations,
said that NATO, by bombing Yugoslavia, has challenged the
authority of the United Nations and the norm of international law.
</P>
<P>
Under the U.N. Charter, any military action against a sovereign
and independent country should first seek the approval of the U.N.
Security Council, which has the primary responsibility for the
maintenance of peace and security in the world.
</P>
<P>
The unilateral NATO military action has put the international
law and order, built since the end of World War II, at stake, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The NATO bombing "is an omen for the future development." If it
cannot be stopped, "the whole world will enter a dark age," the
diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslavia rejects any idea of foreign military or police
presence in the Serbian province of Kosovo, but civilian presence
can be negotiated, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The civilian presence in Kosovo should exclude those from NATO
countries, because aggressors can't be peace makers," he said.
</P>
<P>
China, Russia, India, Latin America and black Africa are
welcome to send their representatives to help the peace process in
Kosovo when the NATO aggression ends, he said.
</P>
<P>
In response to the announced peace efforts by U.N. Secretary-
General Kofi Annan, Jovanovic said his country "welcomes the move,
" but progress can be made only if Annan "acts on his own,
independent from the United States and NATO."
</P>
<P>
Annan Monday announced his plan to visit Germany and Russia
April 26-29 to seek a political solution to the Kosovo problem.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the U.N. chief put forward a five-point initiative,
calling upon Belgrade to immediately end expulsions of ethnic
Albanians from Kosovo, withdraw forces from the province and allow
an international peace-keeping force in the region.
</P>
<P>
Annan said he would urge NATO to suspend its airstrikes if
Yugoslavia complies.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslavia last Friday rejected the key element of Annan's
initiative, disallowing an international military presence in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Jovanovic said Belgrade's invitation to Annan to visit Kosovo
made last year is still open. "So he can get first-hand
information on what is really going on there."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
