<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> About 208 Million Chinese Rise from Poverty in Past 20 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 21 (Xinhua)-- China has made giant strides in
its efforts to relieve poverty in the country, with the number of
people living under poverty line reduced to 42 million last year
from 250 million two decades ago.
</P>
<P>
In 1978, the number of Chinese living below the subsistence
line accounted for one-fourth of the world's total; this
percentage is now one-tenth.
</P>
<P>
Poverty relief gained momentum after 1986 when China
systematically launched campaigns to help the poor who had no
access to electricity and clean drinking water in mountainous
areas.
</P>
<P>
During the 1986-1998 period, the central government invested
over 110 billion yuan in industrial projects aimed at raising the
income of the poor. At the same time, people from every segment of
society began donating more than three billion yuan in cash and
commodities every year.
</P>
<P>
Much effort has been given to improving the quality of the
infrastructure in impoverished regions, as well. The central
government employs local people to build highways, reservoirs, and
power plants, and has paid out some 25 billion yuan worth of grain,
edible oil, clothing and other articles of daily use.
</P>
<P>
China has also actively called on the richer coastal areas to
invest in the western regions, where a majority of the poor live.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the average annual income for poor farmers
rose to more than 1,200 yuan last year, from only 206 yuan in 1986.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990421.0315 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Many Administrative Departments Lose Lawsuits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 21 (Xinhua) -- About one-quarter of Beijing's
administrative departments have lost lawsuits brought against them
by ordinary employees since China's courts began accepting such
litigation a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
Over the past decade, local courts at various levels in Beijing
accepted 3,190 lawsuits lodged by Chinese workers against their
employing administrative organizations, and 3,002 of these cases
were seen through to their conclusions, said local sources.
</P>
<P>
The administrative lawsuit tribunals of the various courts in
China's capital also accepted 6,179 non-litigation cases involving
administrative misconduct, and completed 5,840 of them.
</P>
<P>
The Administrative Procedure Law was adopted at the second
plenary session of the Seventh National People's Congress (NPC) on
April 4, 1989, and became effective on October 1, 1990.
</P>
<P>
The implementation of this law has been widely heralded as an
important step made by China toward building socialist democratic
politics, as the law gives common people a powerful legal tool
with which to seek justice from their employing administrative
organizations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
