<HEADLINE> NATO Has to Talk with Milosevic in End of Kosovo War: Dini </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto
Dini Tuesday warned that the NATO alliance may find it has to
negotiate with Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic in the end of
the Kosovo war.
</P>
<P>
In a testimony to a joint session of the Senate's foreign and
defense committees, he said that "in the end of the crisis, we
cannot rule out having to negotiate with Milosevic."
</P>
<P>
Dini said the next step in the crisis could be a UN Security
Council resolution which repeats the conditions for an end to the
bombing, but also assigns "various tasks, including security
guarantees to the various international organizations."
</P>
<P>
According to Dini, the NATO summit in Washington at the weekend
should make it possible to find an agreement on possible steps in
a negotiating process.
</P>
<P>
He said the summit would agree to still stronger forms of
military action short of the deployment of surface troops in
Kosovo, adding that as far as he knew, sending troops into Kosovo
has not been taken into consideration "at the moment".
</P>
<P>
Dini also confirmed that Italy "plans to keep its embassy in
Belgrade open and maintain diplomatic relations with Belgrade
unless it becomes impossible." 
</P>
