<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Cabinet Approves Budget for Fiscal 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 21 (Xinhua) -- The Thai cabinet approved on
Tuesday an 860-billion-baht (23.2 billion U.S. dollars) budget for
fiscal 2000 beginning October 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The draft -- a 4.2 percent increase from last fiscal year --
will carry a 110-billion-baht (2.97 billion dollars) deficit based
on the government's capability to generate a revenue of only 750
billion baht (20.2 billion dollars) from tax collection.
</P>
<P>
Next year's budget allocations are aimed largely at toning down
the adverse effects of the crisis on the social front, improving
the state administrative system, increasing the potential of
manpower and society for sustainable development and restructuring
the economy to hasten recovery, the Finance Ministry's Budget
Bureau was quoted Wednesday by the Bangkok Post as saying.
</P>
<P>
Expenses for development projects have been set at 483.105
billion baht (13.05 billion dollars), up 1.4 percent from this
fiscal year and is 56.2 percent of next year's budget total, the
bureau said.
</P>
<P>
The largest chunk of the fund, or 222,401 million baht (6.01
billion dollars), will go to education-related causes.
</P>
<P>
The bureau estimated that the economy in 2000 would pick up
but growth would be small averaging 2-3 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
