<HEADLINE> Philippines' Bank Credit Continues to Shrink </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 21 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' economic
activities in the first two months of the year were still weak,
signified by the sustained contraction in bank credit, the
Philippine Post reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Gabriel Singson, governor of the Central Bank of the
Philippines, was quoted as saying deposit credits of the country's
deposit money banks fell by 0.16 percent at the end of February
from the year ago level.
</P>
<P>
Banks of the country remained hesitant to lend out and the
private sector remains wary of borrowing, he said.
</P>
<P>
But the figure indicated an improvement from the credit
contraction of 3.77 percent recorded in January this year, the
newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The central bank has reduced the overnight borrowing and
lending rates by 250 basis points and the liquidity deposit
reserve requirement by 3 percent since the start of the year to
encourage banks to lend more. 
</P>
</TEXT>
