<DOCNO> XIE19990421.0328 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fertilizer in Demand in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Annual production at three local
Myanmar fertilizer plants of about 120,000 tons is unable to meet
the country's demand, said the latest issue of the local Myanmar
Business Magazine.
</P>
<P>
The three fertilizer plants are Kyun Chaung, Salay and Kyaw
Swar.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar needs about 800,000 tons of chemical fertilizer
including 700,000 tons of urea per year, it said.
</P>
<P>
Despite the fact that the Myanmar government procured a large
amount of fertilizer locally and from abroad, it distributed less
to its farmers in fiscal 1997-98.
</P>
<P>
According to an official report on the country's agriculture in
the year, of the 394,000 tons of fertilizer obtained by the
state-run Myanmar Agriculture Service (MAS) and other
organizations, 289,000 tons were distributed, a decrease of 35,000
tons over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The decrease was attributed to the inability of farmers to buy
the fertilizer because of rising prices.
</P>
<P>
In fiscal 1997-98, the MAS distributed 117,000 tons of
fertilizer and 63.9 percent of the total amount was sold to
farmers.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, Myanmar produced 112,087 tons
of urea and imported 34 million U.S. dollars worth of it in 1998,
13 million less than the previous year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990421.0329 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
