<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil's Chicken Export Increases in First Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
External sales over the period from January to March reached
154,722 tons with a value of 188.2 million U.S. dollars, said
Claudio Martins, director of the Brazilian Association of Chicken
Exporters (BACE), according to a local newspaper on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The volume increased 7 percent over the first quarter compared
with the same period last year and the value rose by 13 percent
even with the devaluation of almost 30 percent of the Brazilian
currency against the dollar, according to BACE.
</P>
<P>
The positive results were due to the action of BACE, which
requested its members not to reduce prices drastically for the
exchange parity, said Martins.
</P>
<P>
Chicken exports to Cuba, the Middle East, Hong Kong and Japan
went up. They are traditional buyers of the product, he said.
</P>
<P>
Chicken exports to Argentina, Brazil's main commercial partner,
contracted 15 percent during the period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
