<HEADLINE> IMF Upgrades Australia's Economic Growth Forecasts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 21 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary Fund
(IMF) has revised its growth forecast for Australia to 3.1 percent
for calendar year 1999 from the 2 percent it was predicting four
months ago.
</P>
<P>
Despite the upward revision, the organization noted that
Australia needs to maintain fiscal discipline and said raising
national savings should be a high priority, the Australian
Financial Review reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The financial body also has forecast that Australia's economy
would grow at 3.2 percent in 2000.
</P>
<P>
This compares with its review in November last year, where it
tipped a growth of only 2.5 percent in 1999 and 2 percent in
December, lifting slightly to 2.7 percent in 2000.
</P>
<P>
Australia's economic growth rate reached a surprising 4.7
percent in calendar 1998.
</P>
<P>
The Australian federal government forecast in its mid-year
review that the economy would grow at 3.25 percent for the fiscal
year of 1998-1999, ending on June 30, 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
