<DOCNO> XIE19990421.0348 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: ABCs of Macao SAR Basic Law (43) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 21 (Xinhua) -- Following is part 43 of a
question and answer series on the Basic Law of the Macao Special
Administrative Region (MSAR).
</P>
<P>
Will the MSAR maintain the low tax system previously pursued in
Macao?
</P>
<P>
Macao has all along pursued the low tax policy. Its tax rates
are generally lower than those of other countries or regions
around it, except for tax for franchised businesses.
</P>
<P>
For instance, the income tax is 15 percent to 17 percent in
Hong Kong while that in Macao is only between 2 percent and 15
percent, much lower than 22 percent in Taiwan, 39 percent in
Thailand, 40 percent in Singapore, 52 percent in Japan and 54
percent in the Republic of Korea.
</P>
<P>
Low tax in Macao is compatible with its export-oriented economy.
It helps attract foreign investment, develop its economy and
improve the living standards of its people.
</P>
<P>
To maintain Macao's economic competitiveness and enable its
people to lead a better life along with the growth of its economy,
the Basic Law provides that the MSAR shall institute an
independent taxation system and independently enact laws
concerning taxes brackets, tax rates, tax reductions, and other
tax-related matters by drawing upon the low tax policy previously
pursued in Macao.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990421.0349 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
