<DOCNO> XIE19990421.0358 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "California Fuel Cell Partnership" Announced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Los Angeles, April 20 (Xinhua) -- In an important step forward
for fuel cell electric vehicles, a collaboration between the U.S.
state of California, energy companies and automobile manufacturers
was announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Announcing the "California Fuel Cell Partnership" at a press
conference in Sacramento, California Governor Gray Davis said that
fuel cell vehicles will soon be appearing on the state's streets
and freeways.
</P>
<P>
For the first time ever in the United States, automobile
companies and fuel suppliers have joined the government to
demonstrate fuel cell vehicles under real day to day driving
conditions. Partners include auto manufacturers DaimlerChrysler
and Ford, oil companies ARCO, Shell and Texaco, and fuel cell
company Ballard Power Systems.
</P>
<P>
The partnership will place about 50 fuel cell vehicles -- cars
and buses -- on the road between 2000 and 2003.
</P>
<P>
Fuel cells create their own electricity through a chemical
reaction between hydrogen and oxygen. Fuel cell vehicles have the
potential to compete with conventional cars in passenger space,
performance, driving range, safety and cost. In addition they will
provide good fuel efficiency and lower noise, vibration and air
emissions than vehicles powered by internal combustion engines.
This combination makes fuel cell the most likely alternative
technology to power the vehicles of the next century, according to
California Air Resources Board.
</P>
<P>
In addition to testing the vehicles, the partnership will also
identify fuel infrastructure issues and prepare the California
market for this new technology. Initial demonstration vehicles
will run on hydrogen, directly from tanks on board the vehicles.
Subsequent demonstration vehicles are likely to run on methanol
fuel. Technology for other liquid fuels such as cleaner form of
gasoline will be evaluated. A key goal of the partnership is to
determine the best fuel infrastructure for the market entry of
fuel cell vehicles, which could emerge as soon as 2004.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
