<DOCNO> XIE19990421.0359 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia's Foreign Debt to be Reduced or Rescheduled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 20 (Xinhua) -- Zambian Finance Minister Edith
Nawakwi said here Tuesday that most of donor countries are willing
to either reschedule or reduce a major part of her country's debt
stock due.
</P>
<P>
She said that the Paris Club which met in France last week
favorably considered Zambia's case, notably the options of either
writting off 67 percent of debt due or rescheduling the payment
of debt over a longer period of time.
</P>
<P>
Nawakwi, who returned here Tuesday from the Paris Club meeting
said that the effect of the agreement reached at the meeting means
that her country's due debt of 2.3 billion U.S. dollars will be
reduced to about one billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
She said the Zambian government will implement the enhanced
structural adjustment facility program as the only alternative to
the revitalization of its economy.
</P>
<P>
The successful implementation of the program will qualify
Zambia to access the highly indebted poor countries initiative
(HIPC) resulting in a substantial reduction of its 6.5
billion-dollar foreign debt, she said.
</P>
<P>
She said the International Monetary Fund (IMF) and World Bank
will consider Zambia's request to access the HIPC initiative by
December this year.
</P>
<P>
She said her country is spending 35 percent of its budget to
service debt and urged the donor community to consider giving
debt relief so that the surplus could be ploughed back in the
economy.
</P>
<P>
The minister said her country will maintain a tight fiscal and
monetary economic policy to foster economic growth and qualify for
debt relief by the end of this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
