<DOCNO> XIE19990421.0360 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraqi Oil Exports Below Its Needs, Says U.N. Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 20 (Xinhua) -- A United Nations Official
said on Tuesday that the new estimates of Iraqi oil exports for
the current phase will be still below the U.N. permitted figure
and enadequate to meet many of the needs of Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
Benon Sevan, Executive Director of the U.N. Office of the Iraq
Program which oversees Iraq's oil exports, said the new
estimates based on the price of 14 U.S. dollars a barrel, are more
than 1.7 billion dollars below the U.N. authorized 5.2 billion
dollars for the phase from 26 November 1998 - 24 May 1999.
</P>
<P>
He said the situation in the previous and current phases "has
been far worse creating an overall humanitarian deficit" of more
than 2.5 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
So far in the current phase, Iraq has exported 269.7 million
barrels of crude oil for an average price of 10.09 dollars.
</P>
<P>
At current production rates and assuming the recent rise in the
oil price is sustained, it appears likely that the revenue in the
phase could reach 3.4 billion dollars, the latest U.N. report
said.
</P>
<P>
The Oil-for-Food program started to be implemented in 1996.
Since February last year, the Security Council raised the ceiling
of Iraqi oil exports revenue to 5.2 billion dollars for a phase of
180 days.
</P>
<P>
However, due to its dilapidated oil industry as a result of
economic sanctions and low oil prices, Iraq has been able only to
fetch an export revenue of less than 3 billion dollars in the last
phases. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
